1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:21,000
This is Emilye Crosby and it's May 29, 2017, 2013.

3
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:26,000
I'm here with John Bishop and we're interviewing Mr. (Lonnie C.) King,

4
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:32,000
in one of the Southwest Library grants of the Fortin County Library here in Atlanta

5
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:36,000
as part of the Southern World History Project.

6
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:44,000
Civil Rights History Project sponsored by the Smithsonian Museum of African American History and Culture in the Library of Congress.

7
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:47,000
I think the American History Project.

8
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:54,000
And so Mr. (Lonnie C.) King, we're very pleased that you're with us here today.

9
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:05,000
Well, thank you very much for coming to record my comments about this great era in our history.

10
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:13,000
So you're talking about your family and your early background?

11
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:18,000
Yes, I was born in a little town called Arlington, Georgia,

12
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:23,000
which is down 27 miles southwest of Albany.

13
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:28,000
The county was Calhoun County.

14
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:36,000
My mother's name was Bertha Lee Smith King and she was one of 17 children.

15
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:40,000
My father's name was LC King Senior.

16
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:47,000
He had about seven or eight brothers and brothers and sisters.

17
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:50,000
They divorced when I was about two, I guess.

18
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:55,000
And I stayed with my grandfather until I was eight.

19
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:04,000
My grandfather kept me real until he died and then they sent me to Atlanta to be with my mother.

20
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:15,000
I guess Dr. Emilye Crosby, if I had to pinpoint my beginnings, I have to say I believe that I was born looking up at the bottom.

21
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:19,000
I was not on the bottom. I was looking up at the bottom. I was up there.

22
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:26,000
So the likelihood that I might even go to college,

23
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:30,000
much less finished college and do some other things, was probably a little remote,

24
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:34,000
considering the environment that I grew up in.

25
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:43,000
However, I have to attribute a great deal of my desire for freedom and my passion,

26
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:49,000
and my commitment, and I guess my long distance running attitude to my grandfather,

27
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:54,000
who was my mentor, his Reverend Joseph P. Smith.

28
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:01,000
He was an evangelist who also was a note singer with perfect pitch in his voice.

29
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:04,000
He was a tremendous person.

30
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:15,000
And a lot of my feelings about matters and attitudes about matters today flow from those years,

31
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:19,000
those six years I was under his tutelage.

32
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:28,000
And as I reflect in talking to you now, I guess it's akin to what John Locke once said,

33
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:37,000
that what you teach a child in the first six years of their lives will influence how they're going to be for the rest of their lives.

34
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:40,000
But you write on that blank slate.

35
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:44,000
I guess my granddad wrote a few things on my blank slate.

36
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:54,000
One of the things that I know he wrote on my blank slate was the fact that one day we had to change the system.

37
00:03:54,000 --> 00:04:04,000
I remember in 1942, I was walking home from school in the first grade,

38
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:10,000
and I saw my first plane crop duster, dropped leaflets.

39
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:14,000
That was where they campaigned during those days in rural areas.

40
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:20,000
And so I picked up one of the leaflets and took it home,

41
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:25,000
and I could read every word, understood every word that I read,

42
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:28,000
because he had taught me the read before I went to school.

43
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:32,000
But that was one word that I didn't understand.

44
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:43,000
Now this now, the crop duster was hired by Eugene Talmadge, who was running for governor at that time.

45
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:49,000
I said, granddad, what is a nigger?

46
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:51,000
He said, where'd you get that from?

47
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:56,000
I said, the plane just dropped us and I picked it up.

48
00:04:56,000 --> 00:05:00,000
And I can understand everything, but I have never heard of a nigger.

49
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:03,000
I don't even keep a nigger in his place.

50
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:04,000
Keep the nigger in his place.

51
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:08,000
He said, come on and sit on my knee, let me talk to you.

52
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:14,000
He proceeded to tell me about Talmich and about racism.

53
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:20,000
A comment that he made to me sticks with me today, he said, Dom,

54
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:25,000
you know, we're still in a form of slavery.

55
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:29,000
The difference is that we can go home at night.

56
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:32,000
And we don't have anybody who's that assigned overseer.

57
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:42,000
But for all practical purposes, the system that we're in is one that is oppressive, so forth, and so on.

58
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:53,000
As fate would have it a few weeks later, I happened to be at the kitchen table with he and my grandmother, with him and my grandmother.

59
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:58,000
And I saw these on the lobes on the table.

60
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:01,000
And I was an inquisitive kid.

61
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:14,000
No, Z. I picked it up and I said, granddaddy, what is the national association for the vastness of colored people?

62
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:21,000
He said, that's a national civil rights organization.

63
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:26,000
And I'm recruiting memberships for them.

64
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:30,000
50 cents, I believe at that time.

65
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:36,000
He said, son, one day, this organization's going to set us free.

66
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:41,000
He said, they've got lawyers in New York and so forth and so on.

67
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:47,000
So when you look at that kind of orientation that I heard of preach on Sundays about freedom and so forth and so on,

68
00:06:47,000 --> 00:07:04,000
he was painting on my blank slate or writing on my blank slate a kind of add to resistance added to two racism and discrimination that I think served me well in 1960.

69
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:07,000
What were the churches?

70
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:10,000
Actually, he was an evangelist so he didn't even have a church.

71
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:20,000
He was always on the circuit preaching at different churches all over that part of Southwest Georgia and Northeast Alabama.

72
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:29,000
You might have been younger than those things that you wouldn't have known this, but I think that's right around the time that the basic was traveling around in that area.

73
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:33,000
Do you have any ideas you might have come to?

74
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:39,000
I don't know whether I actually came through there or not. That was 1941-42.

75
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:42,000
She was with the NAACP at that time.

76
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:47,000
She was there coming to think of it.

77
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:50,000
She had two strengths at the NAACP, I think.

78
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:53,000
I think it was a position.

79
00:07:53,000 --> 00:07:56,000
I think I can't remember what they call a person made of steel.

80
00:07:56,000 --> 00:07:59,000
That was fair and direct.

81
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:03,000
I don't know whether my mother, she ever met my grandfather.

82
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:08,000
She probably did, to be honest with you, but I was a little kid.

83
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:11,000
What kind of work did you do when you started doing this?

84
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:13,000
He was a farmer.

85
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:16,000
He was a sharecropper.

86
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:24,000
He had ten acres that he rented from some man that owned the property.

87
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:30,000
They would divide up in the fall, whatever.

88
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:33,000
I don't know whether or not he ever broke even.

89
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:36,000
I just know that he was a sharecropper.

90
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:38,000
I used to go to the field.

91
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:41,000
I was too young to do any work, so I would go and watch him.

92
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:47,000
I never forget an anecdote here.

93
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:52,000
I had ventured down into the corn field part of these ten acres.

94
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:55,000
I ran into a rattlesnake.

95
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:59,000
Of course, I knew to run from a rattlesnake.

96
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:03,000
When I got back to the wagon, I said, Granddaddy,

97
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:07,000
I just ran upon a rattlesnake down here.

98
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:12,000
I said, I just ran a puddle on Granddaddy.

99
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:14,000
I said, I'm going down here.

100
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:18,000
If I don't find a rattlesnake, I'm going to thank you.

101
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:21,000
I said, Granddaddy, you don't think the rattlesnake is going to wait for you to come down there.

102
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:24,000
Do you? Come on.

103
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:27,000
He went down and he didn't find a rattlesnake,

104
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:30,000
but he did not beat me either.

105
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:38,000
These anecdote really do, I guess, make me feel good when I think about the man

106
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:41,000
and what he did for me.

107
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:47,000
One of the things he used to tell me is that you need to always try to tell the truth

108
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:49,000
when something comes up.

109
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:52,000
It's easier to tell the truth than to lie.

110
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:55,000
Because when you lie, you got to remember the lie in order to not get caught in the lie.

111
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:58,000
So just tell the truth and it keeps coming out right.

112
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:02,000
All those kinds of things make a difference when you're young and coming up.

113
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:09,000
It must have been in the past, so you're difficult to do anything that has been passed

114
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:10,000
and passed away.

115
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:13,000
It was terrible.

116
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:15,000
It was terrible.

117
00:10:15,000 --> 00:10:19,000
But I came here at eight years of age and I guess we can move on into Atlanta now.

118
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:24,000
My mother was a member of Ebenezer Baptist Church.

119
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:29,000
So I came in March and they had the spring revival in April.

120
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:33,000
So Martin Luther King Sr opened the doors of the church.

121
00:10:33,000 --> 00:10:37,000
That first night that I went to the revival.

122
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:39,000
My mother was in the choir.

123
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:44,000
So when they opened the doors of the church, I got up and I went down and I joined.

124
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:47,000
I could see my mother looking to me.

125
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:50,000
I had not talked to her about it.

126
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:54,000
And she had some concern I could tell.

127
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:59,000
So when we got on the bus to go home, she said,

128
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:02,000
you didn't tell you to go on the church.

129
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:05,000
I said, well, we didn't talk about it.

130
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:08,000
She said, well, do you know what you're doing?

131
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:10,000
I said, yes, I know what I'm doing.

132
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:12,000
So she didn't say anything more about it.

133
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:15,000
I was shocked that I did it at eight.

134
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:18,000
Anyway.

135
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:29,000
But while I had Ebenezer, I was there from 45 until 54 when I went into the military.

136
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:33,000
My mother, she took me to church almost every day in the week.

137
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:36,000
That was something going on.

138
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:42,000
And when I went to the church, she had me at the YMCA.

139
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:44,000
And I'll cover that later.

140
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:49,000
But anyway, while I was there at Ebenezer Baptist Church,

141
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:54,000
Martin Luther King Sr, Alberta Williams King,

142
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:59,000
was always asking me to lead something, hit something.

143
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:03,000
And that was when I formed something called the Ebenezer Youth Organization

144
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:05,000
that's still running down there now.

145
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:08,000
I was the first chairman of the organized organization.

146
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:11,000
But that's also when I met his children.

147
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:14,000
A.D. (Alfred Daniel) King. and I had a paper route together.

148
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:17,000
And of course, (Martin) Luther King Jr was a little older than A.D. (Alfred Daniel) King.

149
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:20,000
And I always knew that he was going to be a great preacher,

150
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:24,000
because on Thursday nights, while my mother was there,

151
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:27,000
regurghershin downstairs with the choir,

152
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:32,000
he'd be upstairs practicing his preaching.

153
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:35,000
Because that was the pastor, so he could get the key.

154
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:39,000
So Martin King, he's almost like he never played.

155
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:41,000
He was always serious.

156
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:43,000
So he would be in there, you know, did he?

157
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:45,000
Practice, practice, practice.

158
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:47,000
Did you have a lot for me?

159
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:48,000
Did you feed back?

160
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:49,000
No, I didn't.

161
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:51,000
We were just friends.

162
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:53,000
And I guess it probably helped.

163
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:55,000
My name was the same as theirs.

164
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:57,000
And so they knew who I was.

165
00:12:57,000 --> 00:12:59,000
And that may have been reason why the bother kept asking me to do things.

166
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:00,000
So they had the same name.

167
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:03,000
That served me well later on during the movement,

168
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:06,000
which I'm sure we're talking about later on.

169
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:08,000
So it sounds like you really much,

170
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:10,000
very much, you could learn from your black institutions,

171
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:11,000
from my family.

172
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:13,000
Yes, yes.

173
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:15,000
The Butler Street YMCA,

174
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:19,000
and just into the church, my mother,

175
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:22,000
took me down to the Butler Street YMCA,

176
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:25,000
when I was eight, before I even started to school,

177
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:28,000
because she kept me out of school for several months,

178
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:32,000
because I was eight,

179
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:35,000
but I was promoted to the fifth grade,

180
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:38,000
and she felt I was going too fast.

181
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:43,000
And so she had me sit at home from March until September.

182
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:46,000
She said, because if I let you go,

183
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:48,000
you might get promoted to the sixth grade,

184
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:50,000
and you would just be nine.

185
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:52,000
She said, I'm not sure, well, I want to do that.

186
00:13:52,000 --> 00:13:55,000
So I had to sit home and what have you.

187
00:13:56,000 --> 00:14:03,000
But she also went down to the Butler Street YMCA,

188
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:07,000
and he started why this now closed, believe it or not,

189
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:10,000
but it was organized 1890 something.

190
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:15,000
She asked me to go down there,

191
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:17,000
and I went, well, when I just learned,

192
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:19,000
as I've been writing for my dissertation,

193
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:22,000
I interviewed a man who's 85 years old,

194
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:25,000
and I interviewed him because he was around that land,

195
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:29,000
and during that time, I knew he was around the Y.

196
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:33,000
His name is Mr. Eugene Thomas.

197
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:37,000
Very lucid man, retired from the public school system.

198
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:38,000
So I went to see Mr. Thomas,

199
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:45,000
and I said, Mr. Thomas, let me talk to you about my tenure at the Y,

200
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:48,000
and also about Atlanta and the environment in the forties,

201
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:51,000
when you were an adult here,

202
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:54,000
he said, okay, and we talked about all of that,

203
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:57,000
but he said, but specifically, talk about you.

204
00:14:57,000 --> 00:14:58,000
He said, I was there.

205
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:00,000
He was an assistant to Mr. J. D. Winston,

206
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:04,000
who was the director of the What Boys division at that time.

207
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:09,000
And so he told me that my mother came down there

208
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:12,000
to see Mr. Winston in 1945,

209
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:17,000
to tell her that she had a son who was coming in to Atlanta

210
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:19,000
from Odinton, Georgia,

211
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:24,000
and she wanted me to come down there and wanted him to look out for me

212
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:27,000
while I was down there,

213
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:32,000
and that I should not let me leave there until 6 o'clock,

214
00:15:32,000 --> 00:15:35,000
because by that time, you would have chance to get home

215
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:38,000
from her job as a maid,

216
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:44,000
and Mr. Winston agreed to that.

217
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:49,000
I did not know until I talked to Mr. Thomas

218
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:53,000
that she came down there another time,

219
00:15:53,000 --> 00:15:56,000
just to see how things were going,

220
00:15:56,000 --> 00:15:58,000
and more than other Mr. Winston,

221
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:00,000
if I was a good boy or a bad boy,

222
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:01,000
because if I was a bad boy,

223
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:04,000
she was going to whip my line right there.

224
00:16:04,000 --> 00:16:07,000
I said, okay, I didn't know any of this stuff.

225
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:09,000
It was all done behind my back,

226
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:12,000
but I guess for my benefit though.

227
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:14,000
Those were some good times,

228
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:16,000
our young people could,

229
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:20,000
when parents were not necessarily afraid of molestation

230
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:22,000
of their children by people.

231
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:24,000
Nowadays, you have to watch out,

232
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:26,000
you don't know what's going to go on.

233
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:29,000
But during those days, people trusted one another,

234
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:31,000
people looked out for the kids,

235
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:35,000
and then those things had a tremendous bearing on you.

236
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:37,000
So I grew up in the Bell Street,

237
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:40,000
and I left there in 1954.

238
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:43,000
So first of all, I was there so much until they hired me.

239
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:46,000
They hired me down there.

240
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:52,000
At $0.50 a day,

241
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:54,000
and I was just around just helping.

242
00:16:54,000 --> 00:16:57,000
I was a little help around there.

243
00:16:57,000 --> 00:17:01,000
And I knew I had gotten paid $0.50 a day,

244
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:03,000
for basically just kind of being there,

245
00:17:03,000 --> 00:17:05,000
picking up tiles, you name it.

246
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:07,000
And I said, Mr. Thomas,

247
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:10,000
just don't know me.

248
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:15,000
Where did you get the budget to pay me $0.50 a day?

249
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:17,000
He said, there was no budget.

250
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:19,000
I said, well, where did the money come from?

251
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:22,000
He said, we all chipped in $0.50 a piece.

252
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:24,000
In other words, he said, we paid it.

253
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:27,000
The old senior staff put together a little money

254
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:30,000
to pay this $0.89 10-year-old kid.

255
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:32,000
I was shocked that that had happened,

256
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:34,000
but it happened.

257
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:39,000
Dr. Emilye Crosby, I believe,

258
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:40,000
when you're born all done,

259
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:43,000
you look at all these things.

260
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:47,000
God was preparing me for 1960,

261
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:50,000
because while I was at the YMCA

262
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:51,000
for all those years,

263
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:54,000
I ran into all the movers and shakers in Atlanta,

264
00:17:54,000 --> 00:17:55,000
in the Black community.

265
00:17:55,000 --> 00:17:56,000
They were down there playing bridge.

266
00:17:56,000 --> 00:17:59,000
And I'm the little kid around there watching them play bridge,

267
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:00,000
and I learned table tennis,

268
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:02,000
and I taught a lot of them how to play table tennis.

269
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:07,000
I was like a little mascot that was always around.

270
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:10,000
So when the movement thing,

271
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:15,000
when Greensboro erupted,

272
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:17,000
as I reflect back now,

273
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:28,000
I had been prepared for leadership of the movement in Atlanta,

274
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:30,000
because in order to make it work,

275
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:34,000
I had to find a way to merge the town and the gown.

276
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:37,000
And because I had met so many people at the Y,

277
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:39,000
that knew me from when I was a child,

278
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:41,000
that helped me a great deal when I called them

279
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:44,000
to ask, can I get your help?

280
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:51,000
One more thing that I think is important in my development.

281
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:54,000
My mother was amazed,

282
00:18:54,000 --> 00:18:57,000
so she couldn't pay my tuition at Morehouse.

283
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:00,000
I had gone over there on a partial scholarship,

284
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:03,000
but didn't have enough to really have a full scholarship.

285
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:05,000
So I decided to do something that I had said I'd never do,

286
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:07,000
which is to go into military.

287
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:08,000
And I went into the Navy,

288
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:11,000
and I went there because the Navy offered me a chance to come in

289
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:14,000
on what they call a Kitty Cruise.

290
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:16,000
That would be three years.

291
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:17,000
If you win before you 18,

292
00:19:17,000 --> 00:19:20,000
you get out the day before you 21.

293
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:23,000
And so I went in just before I was 18,

294
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:25,000
got out in three years.

295
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:29,000
While I was in the Navy,

296
00:19:29,000 --> 00:19:31,000
I ran in some of the most virulent races

297
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:35,000
that you could ever encounter under the umbrella

298
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:38,000
of the United States of America.

299
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:43,000
When I was in boot camp,

300
00:19:43,000 --> 00:19:46,000
I was the educational pay officer for my 80-some guys

301
00:19:46,000 --> 00:19:48,000
who was in my group.

302
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:52,000
My job was to teach them the three hours,

303
00:19:52,000 --> 00:19:53,000
you know, all of a sudden,

304
00:19:53,000 --> 00:19:56,000
to graduate after 11 weeks.

305
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:00,000
When I finished,

306
00:20:00,000 --> 00:20:04,000
I was in charge of about 20 people who went to

307
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:08,000
the USS Riscanae Actcraft Carrier in California.

308
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:11,000
So I had all the records and everything.

309
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:13,000
So when I got there,

310
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:15,000
and we saluted the office of the day,

311
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:16,000
we came on board,

312
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:19,000
they sent us down to something called the X-1 Division.

313
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:23,000
That's the orientation division for two weeks.

314
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:26,000
So when we finished the orientation division,

315
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:29,000
we went to Virginia.

316
00:20:29,000 --> 00:20:31,000
They then gave us all a billet.

317
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:33,000
They all gave us a job.

318
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:36,000
So I was the only black person

319
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:40,000
of the folks who were 19 white people plus me.

320
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:46,000
Every last white person got a good job

321
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:49,000
by that I mean either as a young man,

322
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:53,000
which is the same as a secretary,

323
00:20:54,000 --> 00:20:56,000
air control and fire control,

324
00:20:56,000 --> 00:20:58,000
when you name it, those jobs that were,

325
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:01,000
that you had some relationship,

326
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:04,000
those jobs to a civilian career,

327
00:21:04,000 --> 00:21:06,000
except two people in the group.

328
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:08,000
Two of us were sent to the deck force,

329
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:14,000
to chip paint and mop and scrub and you name it.

330
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:15,000
That was me.

331
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:19,000
I had to hire GCT in the group,

332
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:22,000
and the young guy from Kentucky,

333
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:24,000
had the lowest GCT.

334
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:27,000
Now I knew all that stuff because I was in charge of the record.

335
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:31,000
So the black guy and the white guy

336
00:21:31,000 --> 00:21:36,000
with the lowest GCT get a sign to the deck force.

337
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:39,000
It's too late to get out by that time,

338
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:41,000
because I'm there.

339
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:45,000
So I go down to begin my work,

340
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:47,000
chip and paint.

341
00:21:47,000 --> 00:21:48,000
Well that wasn't enough.

342
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:51,000
I got a call after I was done about a month

343
00:21:51,000 --> 00:21:54,000
and I was going to be assigned to another job.

344
00:21:54,000 --> 00:21:59,000
And this time I was assigned the job of cleaning the head.

345
00:21:59,000 --> 00:22:05,000
Now the head was the restroom for 200 people

346
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:09,000
who worked in the deck force on the aircraft carrier.

347
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:15,000
That's a jazzed job, basically, you follow me?

348
00:22:15,000 --> 00:22:20,000
So I went up there

349
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:25,000
and I remember something Dr. May said when I was a freshman.

350
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:28,000
He said,

351
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:30,000
when you go to a more house college,

352
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:33,000
you need to do the very best that you can.

353
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:35,000
Whatever job you do,

354
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:38,000
do it better than anybody else other than God.

355
00:22:38,000 --> 00:22:41,000
And if it's your fate to be a lawyer,

356
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:44,000
be the best lawyer, be the best preacher, best doctor.

357
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:46,000
But if fate falls upon you

358
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:49,000
where you have to be a ditch digger,

359
00:22:49,000 --> 00:22:54,000
be the best ditch digger that's ever been born.

360
00:22:54,000 --> 00:22:56,000
And I said, well, mine wasn't ditch digging

361
00:22:56,000 --> 00:22:59,000
but it was cleaning up this restroom.

362
00:22:59,000 --> 00:23:03,000
So I said, let me take his ammunition.

363
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:07,000
And so I went out and I requisitioned paint,

364
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:09,000
brass polish, you name it.

365
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:13,000
And I turned the place into

366
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:18,000
a very nice looking well lit bright bathroom.

367
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:23,000
So therefore, I only had to work maybe a half hour in the morning,

368
00:23:23,000 --> 00:23:26,000
a half hour and a half afternoon after the lunch.

369
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:30,000
The rest of the time I could read books.

370
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:33,000
And I want you to know that what I had created

371
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:37,000
was so appealing to a third class petty officer

372
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:40,000
put in a petition to bump me out of that job

373
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:44,000
and put me back in the deck for us.

374
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:47,000
So you made cleaning the bathroom and you looked like a good job?

375
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:50,000
Any job that you would make in the south,

376
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:55,000
it seems to me that would, that some whites would say,

377
00:23:55,000 --> 00:23:57,000
you know, I'd rather have that job,

378
00:23:57,000 --> 00:23:58,000
put that nigger out of here.

379
00:23:58,000 --> 00:24:00,000
And so that's what happened to me.

380
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:05,000
So then I applied for dental technician school.

381
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:09,000
But you had to have two years left.

382
00:24:09,000 --> 00:24:15,000
So they sent me a acceptance one year,

383
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:20,000
11 months and 29 days to go on my enlistment,

384
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:25,000
which meant that I had to sign up for an additional year.

385
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:27,000
I said, I'm not going to do this.

386
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:29,000
I'm not going to put out with this.

387
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:32,000
As fate would have it,

388
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:38,000
the dispersing office put out a request for someone

389
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:40,000
to become a dispersing clerk striker.

390
00:24:41,000 --> 00:24:45,000
It is a dispersing clerk train E.

391
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:48,000
And I applied for it.

392
00:24:51,000 --> 00:24:55,000
The division officer called me down to have an interview.

393
00:24:55,000 --> 00:24:59,000
I'm an N.S.J.C. Claren, K.L.A.R.E. in.

394
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:02,000
Claren asked me, why did I apply?

395
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:04,000
And I thought I could do the job.

396
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:05,000
Can you type?

397
00:25:05,000 --> 00:25:07,000
I said no, but I can learn how to do it.

398
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:11,000
He said, well, I'm paraphrasing now.

399
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:16,000
He said, we don't want any knee growth down here.

400
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:19,000
All the folks in here from the South,

401
00:25:19,000 --> 00:25:21,000
you know, it would just not be the thing.

402
00:25:21,000 --> 00:25:24,000
I said, wait a minute, my parents paid taxes too,

403
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:26,000
and I just like that, parents.

404
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:29,000
Yeah, but it wouldn't work.

405
00:25:29,000 --> 00:25:35,000
I want you to see them chaperone on the ship

406
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:38,000
and tell them about my flight.

407
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:40,000
He said, do you pay for that?

408
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:42,000
I said, yes, they did.

409
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:46,000
I said, I don't believe I said, yes, they did.

410
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:49,000
He didn't do a thing, but just take the notes down.

411
00:25:51,000 --> 00:25:54,000
So I'm now back on the deck for us.

412
00:25:54,000 --> 00:26:00,000
And I decided that I would ask the division officer

413
00:26:00,000 --> 00:26:04,000
who was over the deck for us for an appointment.

414
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:09,000
And that was a lieutenant, J.G. Horn,

415
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:11,000
H.R.R. Indy from Louisiana.

416
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:13,000
I forgot the name of the town in Louisiana.

417
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:19,000
And I went in and I told him the same thing that I told the chaplain.

418
00:26:21,000 --> 00:26:24,000
J.G. Horn listened to me.

419
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:27,000
He said, come with me.

420
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:31,000
He took me down to that same instant who said,

421
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:34,000
did he want me down there?

422
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:37,000
Lieutenant J.G. Horn said, Mr. King tells me,

423
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:39,000
that was first of all, he said, Mr. King,

424
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:41,000
I was surprised at that.

425
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:46,000
He said, Mr. King said, and he told him the story.

426
00:26:46,000 --> 00:26:48,000
Is that true?

427
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:52,000
He said, well, they don't want him down here.

428
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:55,000
He said something that is true.

429
00:26:55,000 --> 00:27:00,000
Yes, he said, if his name is not in the plan of the day

430
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:03,000
tomorrow, he will be transferred down here.

431
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:05,000
I'm going to go to the chief of the native personnel

432
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:07,000
and get your commission.

433
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:10,000
He said, Mr. King, come with us, go.

434
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:13,000
The next morning, my name is that plan of the day,

435
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:18,000
to be transferred down because of that white man down in Louisiana

436
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:22,000
who stepped up to the plate to tell another white man you're wrong.

437
00:27:22,000 --> 00:27:25,000
You said you were not asking me when you were born?

438
00:27:25,000 --> 00:27:27,000
Nope, so I'm all the time, but he was speaking,

439
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:28,000
I speak, but never.

440
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:29,000
That was nothing.

441
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:31,000
You had a hierarchy.

442
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:37,000
You had the division officer, then you had a chief on petty officer,

443
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:40,000
then you had a first class, then you had a second class,

444
00:27:40,000 --> 00:27:42,000
then you had some third classes.

445
00:27:42,000 --> 00:27:45,000
I was just a little seam on your podium.

446
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:48,000
So no, they didn't really talk to you unless they wanted to see you.

447
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:51,000
They passed by and be friendly, but the point is you had no contact

448
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:52,000
with the person.

449
00:27:52,000 --> 00:27:55,000
Did you think you did that particularly at some point for you?

450
00:27:55,000 --> 00:27:58,000
No, I think he did because I think he thought it was fair,

451
00:27:58,000 --> 00:28:00,000
and I'm not right.

452
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:03,000
Now, I may be wrong, but I'm just telling you what happened.

453
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:05,000
That's how I got down there.

454
00:28:05,000 --> 00:28:09,000
So when I got there, the guys wouldn't talk to me.

455
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:12,000
They were just angry, I guess, because I had broken the cut-align

456
00:28:12,000 --> 00:28:15,000
on that ship.

457
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:21,000
One guy named Welty Wolf from Seattle, Washington,

458
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:27,000
was in that group, and he was a guy who had been to dispersion school,

459
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:31,000
and one day he came over to me and he said,

460
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:35,000
Lonnie, I've been there for weeks now.

461
00:28:35,000 --> 00:28:37,000
I've never been to talk to me anything.

462
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:39,000
I was just there.

463
00:28:39,000 --> 00:28:41,000
He said, I went to dispersion school and said,

464
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:46,000
are you willing to stay on board ship and learn this stuff?

465
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:51,000
I said, yeah, he said, I'll teach you.

466
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:52,000
He said, but it's going to be quite easy.

467
00:28:52,000 --> 00:28:53,000
You can take the exam.

468
00:28:53,000 --> 00:28:55,000
The next exam is in November.

469
00:28:55,000 --> 00:29:02,000
This is August of 1954.

470
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:07,000
August of 1955.

471
00:29:07,000 --> 00:29:12,000
So I started studying all the books and then another guy named John Bloom

472
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:16,000
from Tempe, Arizona, who also was in that group,

473
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:18,000
joined in to help Welty Wolf.

474
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:20,000
He wanted to teach me how to type.

475
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:22,000
Make a long story short.

476
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:25,000
I took the exam with four other white guys,

477
00:29:25,000 --> 00:29:29,000
four third class petty officer in November.

478
00:29:29,000 --> 00:29:33,000
When the results came back, I was only one who passed.

479
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:35,000
So all of a sudden, now they got it.

480
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:37,000
They didn't want down there.

481
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:40,000
Now it's one of the buses.

482
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:43,000
Revolution down there.

483
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:50,000
So I stayed there and I became staff sergeant, or DK5,

484
00:29:50,000 --> 00:29:54,000
and then I got out.

485
00:29:54,000 --> 00:29:57,000
I was talking to a good friend of mine by the name of Everett Render,

486
00:29:57,000 --> 00:30:05,000
R-E-N-D-E-R, who was my manager when I was a prize fatty in the Navy.

487
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:12,000
And I told Everett Render in the folks in the front of aircraft carrier,

488
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:18,000
they call it a folksle, in Hong Kong, China.

489
00:30:18,000 --> 00:30:20,000
Everett was getting out of the Navy.

490
00:30:20,000 --> 00:30:23,000
I was going to be in it a bit longer than he.

491
00:30:23,000 --> 00:30:27,000
Why don't you come to San Francisco because I'm going to be working for Pacific Bell?

492
00:30:27,000 --> 00:30:30,000
I can get your job there.

493
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:32,000
I said, no, I'm going back to Atlanta.

494
00:30:32,000 --> 00:30:34,000
Finish more house.

495
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:36,000
He said, why are you going back down there?

496
00:30:36,000 --> 00:30:39,000
I said, Everett, there's going to come in time.

497
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:43,000
I believe when we're going to throw off the shackle of segregation down there.

498
00:30:43,000 --> 00:30:46,000
And I want to be there.

499
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:50,000
I told him that in 1957.

500
00:30:50,000 --> 00:30:53,000
I got to make sense.

501
00:30:53,000 --> 00:31:03,000
So when I came back to Morehouse in 1957, I played football and it's hope wasn't so on.

502
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:06,000
And therefore I got to know a lot of people.

503
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:12,000
When you went into the Navy, did you have any expectations going in about what kind of environment

504
00:31:12,000 --> 00:31:15,000
would be in terms of racism or opportunity?

505
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:18,000
Well, I think my mother had more than I.

506
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:24,000
I remember now, my mother had to sign for me to go in because I was not 18.

507
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:38,000
And so when we went down to the recruiting officer, my mother said to the recruiting officer,

508
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:45,000
I don't want my son to become a see going bus boy, was what she said.

509
00:31:45,000 --> 00:31:48,000
I didn't know what that was.

510
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:55,000
And so she explained that she didn't want me going to see.

511
00:31:55,000 --> 00:31:59,000
And all I was going to be doing is being a steward's mate serving the officers.

512
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:01,000
So they didn't make me a steward's mate.

513
00:32:01,000 --> 00:32:04,000
They made me a deck force person.

514
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:11,000
Because she told the officer that she was signing those forms to me to go in with the premise

515
00:32:11,000 --> 00:32:16,000
that he would not be a see going bus boy.

516
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:19,000
So she knew what I was going into.

517
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:21,000
And she thought she was protecting me.

518
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:26,000
I guess she did get me from being a see going bus boy, but how about a janitor?

519
00:32:26,000 --> 00:32:27,000
She did put that in.

520
00:32:27,000 --> 00:32:30,000
But anyway, when I came back, I played football.

521
00:32:30,000 --> 00:32:35,000
I played the first string fullback for Morehouse and ran a few touchdowns for them.

522
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:42,000
And that meant then that I knew a lot of people at Morehouse and Spelman, which served me well later.

523
00:32:42,000 --> 00:32:56,000
So when the Greensboro Force sat down February 1st, I was reading the news paper at Jason Milton.

524
00:32:56,000 --> 00:33:04,000
Went to my good friend Joseph Pierce and said, Joe, why don't we organize and do something here?

525
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:07,000
And he read, he said, OK, let's do it.

526
00:33:07,000 --> 00:33:09,000
And I said, let's go talk to the sky over here.

527
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:11,000
I said, I met him in 1957.

528
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:17,000
He was a time magazine intern when he was in high school, so he should be able to write.

529
00:33:17,000 --> 00:33:22,000
We need to have somebody who can write well with us to tell the story as we organize.

530
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:24,000
And that guy was Julian Bond.

531
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:31,000
And so we went to see him and Julian was reluctant at first, but he finally agreed to sign on.

532
00:33:31,000 --> 00:33:34,000
And so the three of us then began to organize.

533
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:36,000
Did you explain the military?

534
00:33:36,000 --> 00:33:38,000
He basically just said that he thought all that happened.

535
00:33:38,000 --> 00:33:42,000
Somebody else would probably do it, but he didn't want to get involved in the facility at that point.

536
00:33:42,000 --> 00:33:47,000
But I just kind of press it in just a little bit and it didn't take too much.

537
00:33:47,000 --> 00:33:49,000
I mean, intellectually he understood it.

538
00:33:49,000 --> 00:33:55,000
But I think I might have caught him off guard at the time I had talked to him.

539
00:33:55,000 --> 00:34:02,000
But when you read this family, his dad is history, you could realize that his dad was a tremendous scholar

540
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:06,000
and wrote a lot of great things about civil rights.

541
00:34:06,000 --> 00:34:14,000
So I think that it was in his blood, but I think I kind of surprised him in the beginning of that.

542
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:24,000
But we held our first meeting of the students at Morehouse, Holandex, about 20-some people came.

543
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:25,000
And, um...

544
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:28,000
How do you mean in particular?

545
00:34:28,000 --> 00:34:34,000
Like how do you mean in the early morning, when you were in school, when you were in college?

546
00:34:34,000 --> 00:34:37,000
Well, I actually started with the people that I knew best. They were football players.

547
00:34:37,000 --> 00:34:40,000
You know, who were blocking for me on Saturday.

548
00:34:40,000 --> 00:34:42,000
A lot of them had come.

549
00:34:42,000 --> 00:34:44,000
And I got people from Clark College to come.

550
00:34:44,000 --> 00:34:49,000
James Feld, who was the head of the SGA over there.

551
00:34:49,000 --> 00:34:55,000
But most of them were from Morehouse, because that was my base.

552
00:34:55,000 --> 00:35:05,000
I learned at that time how extensive the president's apparatus was.

553
00:35:05,000 --> 00:35:10,000
Because I guess within a matter of a day or two I got this call from Mrs...

554
00:35:10,000 --> 00:35:13,000
Well, I actually not a call. She came down to Yates and Milton.

555
00:35:13,000 --> 00:35:16,000
Mrs. Hill was Dr. Maesage's secretary.

556
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:19,000
I don't know her first name, but her name was Hill.

557
00:35:19,000 --> 00:35:24,000
She came into the place where I was and she did this.

558
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:28,000
She said, Mr. King, Mrs. Hill, Dr. Maesage wants to see you.

559
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:33,000
I had three o'clock in the conference room at Harkness Hall.

560
00:35:33,000 --> 00:35:39,000
And she also told you, and Joe Piers.

561
00:35:39,000 --> 00:35:43,000
And we said, I said, we're in trouble now.

562
00:35:43,000 --> 00:35:45,000
They knew exactly who it was.

563
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:47,000
I don't know if there was something in the room.

564
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:50,000
Yeah, yeah, yeah. They had good spies.

565
00:35:50,000 --> 00:35:55,000
Anyway, when we got in the room, all of a sudden,

566
00:35:55,000 --> 00:36:00,000
all of the SGA people from the other place, other schools were there,

567
00:36:00,000 --> 00:36:04,000
along with Julia and Joe Piers and me.

568
00:36:04,000 --> 00:36:12,000
And so, Rufus E. Clement, who was a chairman, Dr. Rufus came into the president of AU,

569
00:36:12,000 --> 00:36:18,000
was chairman of the meeting and of the council of college presidents.

570
00:36:18,000 --> 00:36:24,000
Rufus E. Clement said, well, he laid out that they knew what was going on.

571
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:28,000
And they talked about the evils of segregation and what have you.

572
00:36:28,000 --> 00:36:31,000
But the thesis that they used was that you need it.

573
00:36:31,000 --> 00:36:35,000
You got the NAACP handle this.

574
00:36:35,000 --> 00:36:40,000
They're equipped to do it. They have the lawyers to do it.

575
00:36:40,000 --> 00:36:44,000
Your parents did not send you here to start a revolution.

576
00:36:44,000 --> 00:36:46,000
They sent you to get an education.

577
00:36:46,000 --> 00:36:51,000
You can do the revolution later on.

578
00:36:51,000 --> 00:36:57,000
Dr. Benjamin E. Mays, who was a second senior person, spoke next.

579
00:36:57,000 --> 00:37:02,000
He reiterated Rufus E. Clement's position.

580
00:37:02,000 --> 00:37:05,000
And also, he was a life membership chairman of the NAACP.

581
00:37:05,000 --> 00:37:08,000
And he spoke into Roy Wilkins before the meeting.

582
00:37:08,000 --> 00:37:14,000
And they're going to provide any legal assistance that we need.

583
00:37:14,000 --> 00:37:18,000
Dr. (Albert E.) Manley from Spelman echoed the same position.

584
00:37:18,000 --> 00:37:22,000
Dr. James P. Brawley, the president of Claw,

585
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:30,000
made what I consider to be the most ass-and-eye incumbent of anybody that was made that day.

586
00:37:30,000 --> 00:37:38,000
He said that if we went downtown to sit in that we would embarrass him,

587
00:37:38,000 --> 00:37:43,000
I couldn't believe that and said that, but that's what he said.

588
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:47,000
And then we came to Harry V. Richardson,

589
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:52,000
who was the president of the Interdenominational Theological Center.

590
00:37:52,000 --> 00:38:00,000
Dr. Richardson waited about a good 10 seconds before he said anything.

591
00:38:00,000 --> 00:38:04,000
No classic Baptist preacher, I guess.

592
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:08,000
And he began an unparaphraising.

593
00:38:08,000 --> 00:38:12,000
I think the students are right.

594
00:38:12,000 --> 00:38:21,000
We all looked around because he had broken the commonality that I think was agreed upon by the president before the meeting.

595
00:38:21,000 --> 00:38:25,000
And he went on to knock it out the pop.

596
00:38:25,000 --> 00:38:30,000
And he, in effect, said that it was time for a change.

597
00:38:30,000 --> 00:38:33,000
It's going to be risky.

598
00:38:33,000 --> 00:38:35,000
But he said, I have a PhD.

599
00:38:35,000 --> 00:38:40,000
I'm the president of a major institution of higher education.

600
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:43,000
I can go downtown and spend my money by clothes.

601
00:38:43,000 --> 00:38:45,000
I can buy anything I want to buy down there.

602
00:38:45,000 --> 00:38:52,000
But if I want to stop in the nice restaurant to have a lunch, I can't go in there.

603
00:38:52,000 --> 00:38:54,000
He said, that's not the wrong with that picture.

604
00:38:54,000 --> 00:38:57,000
He said, I support the students.

605
00:38:57,000 --> 00:38:59,000
I could see the president get upset.

606
00:38:59,000 --> 00:39:04,000
But before they could settle down, Dr. Frank Cunningham,

607
00:39:04,000 --> 00:39:07,000
the president of Morris Brown College, spoke up and said,

608
00:39:07,000 --> 00:39:12,000
I agree with Dr. Richardson.

609
00:39:12,000 --> 00:39:16,000
I knew then that we had him split up.

610
00:39:16,000 --> 00:39:18,000
And he made a very eloquent speech.

611
00:39:18,000 --> 00:39:22,000
He was a philosopher.

612
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:28,000
Then Dr. Clemen, I guess while he was thinking, he said, well, who's going to speak for the students?

613
00:39:28,000 --> 00:39:32,000
So everybody looked at me because I was the agitator.

614
00:39:32,000 --> 00:39:35,000
So I started speaking.

615
00:39:35,000 --> 00:39:40,000
And I laid out the premises that this thing is growing.

616
00:39:40,000 --> 00:39:47,000
The AU Center has always been a citadel of learning from African Americans.

617
00:39:47,000 --> 00:39:57,000
And there's no reason why we should be left behind, so forth and so on.

618
00:39:57,000 --> 00:40:03,000
When I finished, Dr. Clemenit said,

619
00:40:03,000 --> 00:40:10,000
we still think you ought to let the NAACP have this thing legally.

620
00:40:10,000 --> 00:40:20,000
However, why don't you write a manifesto and tell the public why you were doing this?

621
00:40:20,000 --> 00:40:24,000
He said, I think you said, you from the AU Center,

622
00:40:24,000 --> 00:40:27,000
we need to have an intellectual document.

623
00:40:27,000 --> 00:40:32,000
That you draft, not us, but you draft, that would set forth,

624
00:40:32,000 --> 00:40:38,000
quiet you were doing, whatever it is you might do later on.

625
00:40:38,000 --> 00:40:43,000
Well, I always knew that that was from his perspective.

626
00:40:43,000 --> 00:40:46,000
He was playing chess with us.

627
00:40:46,000 --> 00:40:49,000
In other words, if you're going to still do this, let me make a chess move here,

628
00:40:49,000 --> 00:40:51,000
and have you write something.

629
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:54,000
If you get all caught up in writing, events might overtake you,

630
00:40:54,000 --> 00:41:00,000
and you just be the philosophers of the movement as opposed to activists in the movement.

631
00:41:00,000 --> 00:41:02,000
That was a part of what I think he said.

632
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:07,000
He also said, the full page ad in all the papers, I will raise the money,

633
00:41:07,000 --> 00:41:11,000
and I'll pay for it. I get it all done.

634
00:41:11,000 --> 00:41:15,000
I accepted the challenge, and I pointed Roslyn Pope to edit it.

635
00:41:15,000 --> 00:41:22,000
I asked Julian to join her, Charles A. Black to join her.

636
00:41:22,000 --> 00:41:25,000
I think it was Marist Dillard not believe I asked to join,

637
00:41:25,000 --> 00:41:30,000
but the bottom line is that all these people I knew had been English majors in some way or another,

638
00:41:30,000 --> 00:41:33,000
and would write a great document.

639
00:41:33,000 --> 00:41:39,000
Roslyn is so brilliant until it's just unreal how brilliant she is,

640
00:41:39,000 --> 00:41:42,000
but you never know it unless you just sit down and talk to her one day.

641
00:41:42,000 --> 00:41:45,000
She just stopped the kind that goes around and brag.

642
00:41:45,000 --> 00:41:51,000
But that document was written, well, actually what happened is Roslyn called me

643
00:41:51,000 --> 00:41:56,000
tonight before we go back and show her to the president for their approval.

644
00:41:56,000 --> 00:42:01,000
She called me and she said, lining, the committee at your point had not done a thing.

645
00:42:01,000 --> 00:42:05,000
She said, Julian got me some data from a second look.

646
00:42:05,000 --> 00:42:09,000
She said, but the others haven't done anything.

647
00:42:09,000 --> 00:42:11,000
I said, Roslyn, it's show time.

648
00:42:11,000 --> 00:42:16,000
We've got to have a document for the president in the morning to write the damn thing.

649
00:42:16,000 --> 00:42:19,000
So she said, okay, so she wrote it.

650
00:42:19,000 --> 00:42:24,000
And then she typed it at Dr. Zin's house, Howard Zinn.

651
00:42:24,000 --> 00:42:31,000
I think Julian may have typed it, but they used Zin's typewriter to get it done.

652
00:42:31,000 --> 00:42:36,000
So when we read it to the president's saw it the next day,

653
00:42:36,000 --> 00:42:40,000
they were very pleased at the document.

654
00:42:40,000 --> 00:42:43,000
The matter made one or two comments, by and large,

655
00:42:43,000 --> 00:42:47,000
about 9.5% of what Roslyn had written everybody agreed with.

656
00:42:47,000 --> 00:42:52,000
It was published, Clinton had raised $12,000 to pay for the stuff.

657
00:42:52,000 --> 00:42:58,000
And it cost about $4,000 and he had $8,000 left there for our benefit if we needed it.

658
00:42:58,000 --> 00:43:02,000
And it was publishing that Lana Journal, that Lana Constitution,

659
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:05,000
and I believe that Lana daily were on.

660
00:43:05,000 --> 00:43:09,000
Dr. Clinton, I think told me that Mr. Scott, who had the line of work,

661
00:43:09,000 --> 00:43:14,000
black newspaper, wanted cash up front before he would run it.

662
00:43:14,000 --> 00:43:16,000
But the white papers sent him a bill.

663
00:43:16,000 --> 00:43:18,000
He was upset about that.

664
00:43:18,000 --> 00:43:28,000
But anyway, that publication though ended up being reprinted in the New York Times full page free.

665
00:43:28,000 --> 00:43:35,000
The Nation Magazine ran it on, we did it on the 9th of March,

666
00:43:35,000 --> 00:43:43,000
the Nation Magazine ran it, full page added in there, magazine on the 2nd of April 1960.

667
00:43:43,000 --> 00:43:47,000
The Harvard Crimson, Harvard Crimson ran it.

668
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:51,000
The Senate's Jacob Jabb had read into the Congressional record.

669
00:43:51,000 --> 00:43:54,000
And it's for that, for posterity right now.

670
00:43:54,000 --> 00:44:00,000
And it's been used all around the world by a lot of different people.

671
00:44:00,000 --> 00:44:06,000
And guess the imitation is, I happen to be looking, doing some research work at recent,

672
00:44:06,000 --> 00:44:08,000
on this area, in the area.

673
00:44:08,000 --> 00:44:18,000
And lo and behold, I found a document that had been written by Miles College students in 1962.

674
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:27,000
And it basically was nothing but the appeal of a human rights retitle this we believe.

675
00:44:27,000 --> 00:44:33,000
And Atlanta had been taken out and Birmingham had been put in.

676
00:44:34,000 --> 00:44:38,000
I told Ross, and I said, Ross, the imitation is the best form of flattery.

677
00:44:38,000 --> 00:44:47,000
But anyway, we started this movement, and I explained a lot there in those documents.

678
00:44:47,000 --> 00:44:52,000
Now, should I give you the narrative about what happened, or you're going to use the narrative,

679
00:44:52,000 --> 00:44:55,000
or what? Sure, sure.

680
00:44:55,000 --> 00:44:58,000
May 17th, the boycott.

681
00:44:58,000 --> 00:45:00,000
Now, I'm trying to figure out, do you want me to ask you those questions,

682
00:45:00,000 --> 00:45:03,000
or should I just keep talking? Because I can talk on and on about it.

683
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:07,000
I know, we know there's so much, and so many of us are like to have you, you know, keep going,

684
00:45:07,000 --> 00:45:11,000
so narrative, and come back, but it's on.

685
00:45:11,000 --> 00:45:17,000
So when the president brought you all in, you and your peers, and really, and you're,

686
00:45:17,000 --> 00:45:19,000
the same by the president.

687
00:45:19,000 --> 00:45:21,000
And vice president, out of secretary, I think.

688
00:45:21,000 --> 00:45:23,000
Three from each school.

689
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:24,000
Three from each school. Right.

690
00:45:24,000 --> 00:45:27,000
Did they decide to get the student government?

691
00:45:27,000 --> 00:45:30,000
The president, the president did that, we didn't.

692
00:45:30,000 --> 00:45:34,000
Yeah, okay. And because I know I was talking to a few people, and they said that, you know,

693
00:45:34,000 --> 00:45:38,000
some of the presidents will really never involve others in signing the documents,

694
00:45:38,000 --> 00:45:42,000
and that one of them chose not to sign it, but to come there.

695
00:45:42,000 --> 00:45:46,000
Or you mean the president of the student government associations? Yes, that's true.

696
00:45:46,000 --> 00:45:52,000
The guy named Hickman, who was making Georgia, had a methodist,

697
00:45:52,000 --> 00:45:56,000
I think the white methodist in making had given him a scholarship to come in Morris Brown.

698
00:45:56,000 --> 00:46:01,000
And so he was afraid of losing his scholarship. And so Marion signed it, and as a secretary.

699
00:46:01,000 --> 00:46:06,000
When, you know, out of that viewpoint of the community,

700
00:46:06,000 --> 00:46:09,000
you should try to write this, and then write this for a bunch of millions.

701
00:46:09,000 --> 00:46:11,000
Most of it, yeah.

702
00:46:11,000 --> 00:46:15,000
And then I know at a certain point there's a committee on a peer.

703
00:46:15,000 --> 00:46:17,000
That started right after that.

704
00:46:17,000 --> 00:46:24,000
And so how did you, you know, I'm very interested in who emerged that the leader,

705
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:29,000
and how that happened. You know, these people were in official leadership position,

706
00:46:29,000 --> 00:46:33,000
those athletes, the student government, and those people that they're converted,

707
00:46:33,000 --> 00:46:37,000
so they're kind of like, well, let me see if I can answer that this way.

708
00:46:40,000 --> 00:46:43,000
Once we published the appeal,

709
00:46:44,000 --> 00:46:49,000
at about the time the publisher appeared, the best way I can answer this.

710
00:46:49,000 --> 00:46:52,000
That was a Rump group headed by Dr. Lonnie Cross, who was a PhD at Mathematics at AU.

711
00:46:52,000 --> 00:46:56,000
He took his scholarship,

712
00:46:56,000 --> 00:47:01,000
and he was down there to sit in that richest before we could get there.

713
00:47:01,000 --> 00:47:03,000
Yeah.

714
00:47:03,000 --> 00:47:06,000
I'm just documentation.

715
00:47:06,000 --> 00:47:08,000
Oh, no, I'm just, I'm just, yeah.

716
00:47:08,000 --> 00:47:12,000
So what happened is that the president of the university,

717
00:47:12,000 --> 00:47:16,000
the president of the university,

718
00:47:16,000 --> 00:47:19,000
the president of the university,

719
00:47:19,000 --> 00:47:21,000
the president of the university,

720
00:47:21,000 --> 00:47:24,000
the newspaper of the university,

721
00:47:24,000 --> 00:47:28,000
and the president of the university.

722
00:47:28,000 --> 00:47:29,000
Yeah.

723
00:47:29,000 --> 00:47:31,000
Oh, no, I'm just, I'm just really interested.

724
00:47:31,000 --> 00:47:32,000
So what happened is that it was,

725
00:47:32,000 --> 00:47:34,000
the campus was buzzing with all the activity,

726
00:47:34,000 --> 00:47:36,000
so they knew what was going on.

727
00:47:36,000 --> 00:47:39,000
So he wanted to get there

728
00:47:39,000 --> 00:47:43,000
and put his name down before we got there.

729
00:47:43,000 --> 00:47:50,000
My position was that all the schools should come together

730
00:47:50,000 --> 00:47:53,000
which we later on did after it was published.

731
00:47:54,000 --> 00:47:58,000
But prior to that, he had pulled this little city in down there,

732
00:47:58,000 --> 00:48:01,000
with his history, maybe five or six other.

733
00:48:04,000 --> 00:48:07,000
And so I contacted Rufus E. Clement

734
00:48:08,000 --> 00:48:12,000
and raised with him the spectator.

735
00:48:12,000 --> 00:48:15,000
We couldn't afford to have clock going down one day,

736
00:48:15,000 --> 00:48:18,000
a.U. another day, Mays von another day.

737
00:48:18,000 --> 00:48:21,000
I said, that is a divide and conqueror.

738
00:48:21,000 --> 00:48:23,000
If ever I've seen one.

739
00:48:23,000 --> 00:48:25,000
I said, it's because all you're going to do is have the virtues say,

740
00:48:25,000 --> 00:48:28,000
well, who do I negotiate with?

741
00:48:28,000 --> 00:48:30,000
Morris Brown or Morehouse?

742
00:48:30,000 --> 00:48:32,000
I said, we need to have a one voice.

743
00:48:32,000 --> 00:48:34,000
I said, what's the common denominator here?

744
00:48:34,000 --> 00:48:37,000
The common denominator is that we're all African-Americans,

745
00:48:37,000 --> 00:48:38,000
or Negroes.

746
00:48:38,000 --> 00:48:40,000
We're all being subjected to the same kind of discrimination

747
00:48:40,000 --> 00:48:43,000
by the same institutions downtown.

748
00:48:43,000 --> 00:48:47,000
So to go down there now with these divided voices makes no sense.

749
00:48:48,000 --> 00:48:50,000
Clement agreed with me.

750
00:48:50,000 --> 00:48:55,000
He called an all campus meeting down at

751
00:48:55,000 --> 00:49:01,000
at Wehrhal, E.A. Wehrhal, which is on the campus.

752
00:49:01,000 --> 00:49:05,000
And had all A.U. students come to hear him and me.

753
00:49:05,000 --> 00:49:12,000
So Rufus E. Clement gave the exposition as the wider meeting

754
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:14,000
was being held.

755
00:49:15,000 --> 00:49:21,000
And he argued that we ought to be together.

756
00:49:21,000 --> 00:49:23,000
That's the position that we've taken.

757
00:49:23,000 --> 00:49:27,000
And the presence of Wehrhal and we ought to do it as one body.

758
00:49:27,000 --> 00:49:32,000
And he was saying to Dr. Cross, it is kind of productive

759
00:49:32,000 --> 00:49:34,000
for you to take your class down and do this.

760
00:49:34,000 --> 00:49:37,000
So we got to, you know, I got to say to all of you, don't do that.

761
00:49:37,000 --> 00:49:41,000
Let's do it in some kind of organized fashion.

762
00:49:41,000 --> 00:49:45,000
And so he said, line up, we just plain to them what you're

763
00:49:45,000 --> 00:49:46,000
going to try to do.

764
00:49:46,000 --> 00:49:49,000
And so I gave the exposition.

765
00:49:49,000 --> 00:49:55,000
Dr. Cross, when I finished jumped up and challenged me,

766
00:49:55,000 --> 00:49:58,000
and he challenged the right to, as a professor,

767
00:49:58,000 --> 00:50:00,000
to take his class downtown.

768
00:50:00,000 --> 00:50:03,000
And he wasn't going to listen to any of this, dude, you know, okay?

769
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:07,000
So Rufus E. Clement said to him,

770
00:50:07,000 --> 00:50:11,000
Dr. Cross, would you sit down?

771
00:50:11,000 --> 00:50:15,000
So cross that down.

772
00:50:15,000 --> 00:50:18,000
And then I spoke, then Cross jumped up again.

773
00:50:18,000 --> 00:50:23,000
So Clement said, Dr. Cross, would you sit down?

774
00:50:23,000 --> 00:50:26,000
And Cross tried to get a little bit subordinate with him.

775
00:50:26,000 --> 00:50:31,000
Clement said, Dr. Cross, sit down.

776
00:50:31,000 --> 00:50:34,000
I knew then that Cross had been fired, okay?

777
00:50:35,000 --> 00:50:38,000
You don't do that to those guys doing that period of time.

778
00:50:38,000 --> 00:50:41,000
So Cross contract was not renewed in May.

779
00:50:41,000 --> 00:50:44,000
So I knew he was dead as a result.

780
00:50:44,000 --> 00:50:48,000
But Clement backed us, backed me and us, all of us,

781
00:50:48,000 --> 00:50:51,000
about the idea of putting a coalition together.

782
00:50:51,000 --> 00:50:56,000
And so after the appeal was published, we sat down in that same conference room

783
00:50:56,000 --> 00:50:59,000
and decided that every school would have three representatives

784
00:50:59,000 --> 00:51:02,000
on this policy council.

785
00:51:02,000 --> 00:51:12,000
And then the 18 members would pick a chairperson.

786
00:51:12,000 --> 00:51:15,000
And then that chairperson, then that school

787
00:51:15,000 --> 00:51:19,000
from which the chairperson comes can send another person.

788
00:51:19,000 --> 00:51:22,000
So I was chosen to be the original chairman, found in chairman,

789
00:51:22,000 --> 00:51:24,000
I guess you would call it.

790
00:51:24,000 --> 00:51:27,000
And so therefore another person from Morehouse could be added to it.

791
00:51:27,000 --> 00:51:31,000
So ended up being Don Clark, he's the president of SGA.

792
00:51:31,000 --> 00:51:40,000
Julian Bond, and Abadd Branson, who I think he was vice president SGA.

793
00:51:40,000 --> 00:51:42,000
But that's only for Morehouse, of course.

794
00:51:42,000 --> 00:51:45,000
That's really interesting.

795
00:51:45,000 --> 00:51:52,000
So at that point, President Clement, although he was trying to slow you down

796
00:51:52,000 --> 00:52:02,000
a little bit, I think he was trying to slow you down a little bit.

797
00:52:02,000 --> 00:52:05,000
So he was just a strategic decision that this is going to happen.

798
00:52:05,000 --> 00:52:08,000
And if it's going to happen, this is the best way.

799
00:52:08,000 --> 00:52:09,000
I think so.

800
00:52:09,000 --> 00:52:10,000
Yes.

801
00:52:10,000 --> 00:52:15,000
I think he realized that the events had overcome their authority.

802
00:52:15,000 --> 00:52:21,000
They were concerned about losing their tax incentives status.

803
00:52:21,000 --> 00:52:27,000
And that's why I thought it was a legitimate, it was until recently when I started doing research.

804
00:52:27,000 --> 00:52:33,000
The governor of Georgia, Ernest Van der La, when the appeal was published,

805
00:52:33,000 --> 00:52:40,000
said that that document could not have been written by college students anywhere in America.

806
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:44,000
It had to be written by somebody from Moscow.

807
00:52:44,000 --> 00:52:51,000
And what I learned is that he instructed Eugene Cook, who was a Attorney General,

808
00:52:51,000 --> 00:52:59,000
to check on the 501C3 status of all the HBCUs.

809
00:52:59,000 --> 00:53:01,000
So I'm going to pick up the documents on that.

810
00:53:01,000 --> 00:53:06,000
But the bottom line is that they were under siege, which we did door by at the time.

811
00:53:06,000 --> 00:53:12,000
They were risking their 501C3 status, at least the state part of it, okay?

812
00:53:12,000 --> 00:53:22,000
But you know, there must have been a serious conflict in the minds of the college presidents.

813
00:53:22,000 --> 00:53:26,000
When you think about what Dr. Richardson said,

814
00:53:26,000 --> 00:53:30,000
with all this training, climate from Wisconsin,

815
00:53:30,000 --> 00:53:33,000
maize from Bates and New York Chicago,

816
00:53:33,000 --> 00:53:36,000
all these people, all of this education,

817
00:53:36,000 --> 00:53:38,000
and that was a ceiling.

818
00:53:38,000 --> 00:53:41,000
You know, you could just go so far.

819
00:53:41,000 --> 00:53:47,000
And the duality of the part of the folk who ran the system,

820
00:53:47,000 --> 00:53:49,000
that duality didn't bother them at all.

821
00:53:49,000 --> 00:53:54,000
That's just the way I suppose to be in this culture.

822
00:53:54,000 --> 00:53:59,000
Dr. Cross, I see this whole thing as a kin to,

823
00:53:59,000 --> 00:54:05,000
that period, as a kin to a volcano,

824
00:54:05,000 --> 00:54:10,000
in the sense that it was simmering below the surface to all these things,

825
00:54:10,000 --> 00:54:19,000
the different, I guess you would say,

826
00:54:19,000 --> 00:54:32,000
different systems up under the surface were going on,

827
00:54:32,000 --> 00:54:35,000
the dangerous powerful.

828
00:54:35,000 --> 00:54:39,000
But you couldn't see it because the cultural sites that

829
00:54:39,000 --> 00:54:42,000
you hid the oppression, it was there,

830
00:54:42,000 --> 00:54:45,000
but you hid how you felt about it.

831
00:54:45,000 --> 00:54:52,000
And I think that when the young men sat down in Greensboro,

832
00:54:52,000 --> 00:54:55,000
that was the catalyst.

833
00:54:55,000 --> 00:55:02,000
That was the one thing that caused the volcano to erupt.

834
00:55:02,000 --> 00:55:05,000
And I don't see any other way you can answer it,

835
00:55:05,000 --> 00:55:13,000
and 120 days, 70,000 black kids were raising sand all over the south,

836
00:55:13,000 --> 00:55:17,000
because segregation was ubiquitous, it existed everywhere.

837
00:55:17,000 --> 00:55:21,000
And so I think that along with the Second World War,

838
00:55:21,000 --> 00:55:23,000
where a lot of veterans came back,

839
00:55:23,000 --> 00:55:25,000
and when you think about it,

840
00:55:25,000 --> 00:55:30,000
it says, my dad, the veterans of the Second World War

841
00:55:30,000 --> 00:55:33,000
had children that were going to school at that time.

842
00:55:33,000 --> 00:55:36,000
And where could you get a better set of chalk troops,

843
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:38,000
people who were in school, they were waiting at home time,

844
00:55:38,000 --> 00:55:43,000
most of them, and therefore the normal oppressive means

845
00:55:43,000 --> 00:55:45,000
for keeping niggers in that place,

846
00:55:45,000 --> 00:55:50,000
you could not implore it because if the kid is from Miami,

847
00:55:50,000 --> 00:55:53,000
how are you going to get folks in Miami to fire his mama,

848
00:55:53,000 --> 00:55:55,000
or the other place?

849
00:55:55,000 --> 00:55:58,000
But they tried it now because if you go back and look at what happened

850
00:55:58,000 --> 00:56:01,000
during that time, every time we got arrested,

851
00:56:01,000 --> 00:56:04,000
they put our name, rank, and serial number in the paper.

852
00:56:04,000 --> 00:56:07,000
Even in my case, they put down, I lived at 211, 75,

853
00:56:07,000 --> 00:56:10,000
and go on the road, or apartment number, 2A,

854
00:56:10,000 --> 00:56:13,000
just to make sure you knew where he was.

855
00:56:13,000 --> 00:56:16,000
I don't know if you'll never hear.

856
00:56:16,000 --> 00:56:24,000
My mother was scared to death, but was supportive.

857
00:56:24,000 --> 00:56:27,000
Let me tell you two things about my mother that I think

858
00:56:27,000 --> 00:56:30,000
are important for this.

859
00:56:32,000 --> 00:56:39,000
When between March the 15th and May 17th of 1960,

860
00:56:39,000 --> 00:56:43,000
I was having some difficulty getting people organized

861
00:56:43,000 --> 00:56:47,000
in terms of numbers beyond the 30, 40, or 50,

862
00:56:47,000 --> 00:56:52,000
and I knew I needed more than that in order to make this work.

863
00:56:52,000 --> 00:56:56,000
I was talking to my mother, but I said,

864
00:56:56,000 --> 00:57:00,000
mama, I need more people.

865
00:57:00,000 --> 00:57:02,000
She said, you've been all the way, I said,

866
00:57:02,000 --> 00:57:04,000
I've been to the campus, but I need more people.

867
00:57:04,000 --> 00:57:06,000
She said, well, people are afraid.

868
00:57:06,000 --> 00:57:11,000
She said, go over to Spelman.

869
00:57:11,000 --> 00:57:14,000
She said, the ladies will probably know who you are

870
00:57:14,000 --> 00:57:17,000
because of your football staff.

871
00:57:17,000 --> 00:57:20,000
She can't you organize and get the Spelman women behind you

872
00:57:20,000 --> 00:57:23,000
because if you get the Spelman women behind you,

873
00:57:23,000 --> 00:57:26,000
the more hot men are going to come because of the girls.

874
00:57:26,000 --> 00:57:28,000
The Cloud folks will come, March Brown.

875
00:57:28,000 --> 00:57:31,000
And so as fate would have it, you see Dr. Krossbissum,

876
00:57:31,000 --> 00:57:34,000
when you go back and reflect on this then you said,

877
00:57:34,000 --> 00:57:37,000
you know, that's a divine hand in all of this

878
00:57:37,000 --> 00:57:39,000
because let me tell you what else happened.

879
00:57:39,000 --> 00:57:45,000
I got a telephone call from Dr. Albert E. Manley.

880
00:57:45,000 --> 00:57:49,000
Dr. Roer Wilkins was coming to town to speak its Spelman.

881
00:57:49,000 --> 00:57:55,000
Around the first of April.

882
00:57:55,000 --> 00:58:01,000
And he wanted me to come and present this student's view.

883
00:58:01,000 --> 00:58:04,000
The issue was should we go back to class basically.

884
00:58:04,000 --> 00:58:11,000
And so, and so, and so, Manley and Wilkins,

885
00:58:11,000 --> 00:58:15,000
they were taking the affirmative position.

886
00:58:15,000 --> 00:58:18,000
And they wanted me to come and argue the negative position.

887
00:58:18,000 --> 00:58:24,000
And so, I was scared to death.

888
00:58:24,000 --> 00:58:29,000
Yes, it's imposing to go and debate a man

889
00:58:29,000 --> 00:58:32,000
with international reputation like Roer Wilkins.

890
00:58:32,000 --> 00:58:39,000
Swal, well educated, been at this, been at this stuff for 30 some years.

891
00:58:39,000 --> 00:58:42,000
So here we are, three of us up there on the stage

892
00:58:42,000 --> 00:58:46,000
and the place is packed with all ladies from Spelman.

893
00:58:46,000 --> 00:58:51,000
So, Dr. Albert E. Manley introduced Dr. Roer Wilkins.

894
00:58:51,000 --> 00:58:54,000
And Roer Wilkins knocked it out the paw.

895
00:58:54,000 --> 00:58:58,000
I mean, he was smoothed it silk.

896
00:58:58,000 --> 00:59:00,000
Oh God!

897
00:59:00,000 --> 00:59:05,000
But I remember I had a course in public speaking at Spelman

898
00:59:05,000 --> 00:59:07,000
is to interesting enough.

899
00:59:07,000 --> 00:59:12,000
And the guy, Dr. Dr. Cothrin said,

900
00:59:12,000 --> 00:59:17,000
if you think you've been outgun in a debate,

901
00:59:17,000 --> 00:59:20,000
learn how to dam it with faint praise.

902
00:59:20,000 --> 00:59:23,000
He said, give them that do.

903
00:59:23,000 --> 00:59:25,000
And then you do your however.

904
00:59:25,000 --> 00:59:29,000
And so, I used my public training that I got from him.

905
00:59:29,000 --> 00:59:33,000
And when I got up, I praised Mr. Wilkins like you wouldn't believe.

906
00:59:33,000 --> 00:59:35,000
But it was all true now.

907
00:59:35,000 --> 00:59:38,000
All the stuff that they had done, I mean I laid it out.

908
00:59:38,000 --> 00:59:42,000
And so, I was like, I was making his speech all over again.

909
00:59:42,000 --> 00:59:46,000
But then I pivoted.

910
00:59:46,000 --> 00:59:51,000
And I made the speech about the time had come.

911
00:59:51,000 --> 00:59:56,000
And I would order and I used a little ration technique on that.

912
00:59:56,000 --> 00:59:59,000
And I ended up saying, Mr. Wilkins,

913
00:59:59,000 --> 01:00:04,000
if not now, when, and if not us, who?

914
01:00:04,000 --> 01:00:05,000
And I sat down.

915
01:00:05,000 --> 01:00:09,000
And the girls went, wow.

916
01:00:09,000 --> 01:00:11,000
Mr. Wilkins did this.

917
01:00:11,000 --> 01:00:14,000
He said, really?

918
01:00:14,000 --> 01:00:19,000
He and I, I guess you were saying the same page.

919
01:00:19,000 --> 01:00:22,000
We had some other deal, I'm dealing with later on.

920
01:00:22,000 --> 01:00:25,000
But those latest came and the rest is history.

921
01:00:25,000 --> 01:00:28,000
I mean, on May 17th when we had that big march here,

922
01:00:28,000 --> 01:00:31,000
we had almost 4,000 people going downtown.

923
01:00:31,000 --> 01:00:34,000
We weeped at Spelman's campus and Morehouse' campus.

924
01:00:34,000 --> 01:00:37,000
I was asking about that.

925
01:00:37,000 --> 01:00:43,000
I was wondering if you know what I was doing with research.

926
01:00:43,000 --> 01:00:45,000
And I was just preliminary.

927
01:00:45,000 --> 01:00:49,000
But one thing I'm very interested in is women's role in all of it.

928
01:00:49,000 --> 01:00:51,000
Okay.

929
01:00:51,000 --> 01:00:55,000
And so of course, Atlanta is a wonderful place to look at that.

930
01:00:55,000 --> 01:00:59,000
Because it seems like great participation.

931
01:00:59,000 --> 01:01:01,000
But it's unherald.

932
01:01:01,000 --> 01:01:02,000
It has not been written.

933
01:01:02,000 --> 01:01:05,000
Okay, go on.

934
01:01:05,000 --> 01:01:08,000
Well, we talk about that time.

935
01:01:08,000 --> 01:01:12,000
So I don't know enough to know whether this is actually accurate.

936
01:01:12,000 --> 01:01:20,000
But impressionistically, it looks like there's a maybe disproportionate number of Spelman participants relative to some of the other campuses.

937
01:01:20,000 --> 01:01:21,000
Absolutely.

938
01:01:21,000 --> 01:01:22,000
Is that true?

939
01:01:22,000 --> 01:01:23,000
Absolutely.

940
01:01:23,000 --> 01:01:29,000
I have identified 169 Spelman ladies who actually went to jail or were out there risking things.

941
01:01:29,000 --> 01:01:32,000
Now that was a whole lot more than that involved in the picket thing and stuff.

942
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:35,000
But those who actually went to jail, I think it was 169.

943
01:01:35,000 --> 01:01:38,000
No more host than anyone close to that.

944
01:01:38,000 --> 01:01:40,000
My Morehouse would be number two.

945
01:01:40,000 --> 01:01:43,000
The clock would be number three.

946
01:01:43,000 --> 01:01:45,000
Marsh Brown number four.

947
01:01:45,000 --> 01:01:48,000
But Spelman, my mom was right.

948
01:01:48,000 --> 01:01:50,000
The Spelman ladies will make it happen.

949
01:01:50,000 --> 01:01:53,000
If they get behind you, they'll make it happen.

950
01:01:53,000 --> 01:01:56,000
Do you have an explanation for why they were so responsive?

951
01:01:56,000 --> 01:01:59,000
I mean, obviously you can't be getting this great talk.

952
01:01:59,000 --> 01:02:01,000
But you could do that at Morehouse, right?

953
01:02:01,000 --> 01:02:02,000
Or one of the other campuses?

954
01:02:02,000 --> 01:02:05,000
I couldn't care as many men as I could care where men at that time.

955
01:02:05,000 --> 01:02:08,000
I'm just going to be honest with you.

956
01:02:08,000 --> 01:02:10,000
Women don't have something else.

957
01:02:10,000 --> 01:02:13,000
Women don't have something else.

958
01:02:13,000 --> 01:02:22,000
And Morehouse, I think I ran into a lot of jealousy from other young men,

959
01:02:22,000 --> 01:02:24,000
who position was.

960
01:02:24,000 --> 01:02:28,000
You know, the line that was not elected president of the SGA.

961
01:02:28,000 --> 01:02:30,000
So why don't we follow in him?

962
01:02:30,000 --> 01:02:33,000
You know, but no way else was risking their life but me.

963
01:02:33,000 --> 01:02:36,000
But nevertheless, I think that was a part of it.

964
01:02:36,000 --> 01:02:41,000
I think it was Mayo, Jalusis, some of it.

965
01:02:41,000 --> 01:02:47,000
We're talking about Morehouse Spelman participation.

966
01:02:47,000 --> 01:02:49,000
The women in that Spelman, I think,

967
01:02:49,000 --> 01:02:56,000
they were the backbone of the movement in my opinion.

968
01:02:56,000 --> 01:03:01,000
Women don't get hung up on who's the leader.

969
01:03:01,000 --> 01:03:08,000
They, if there's a job to be done, and they want to do that job,

970
01:03:08,000 --> 01:03:09,000
they will get involved.

971
01:03:09,000 --> 01:03:12,000
They don't get caught up on who's doing it.

972
01:03:12,000 --> 01:03:17,000
Also, women don't mind following the man.

973
01:03:17,000 --> 01:03:19,000
I mean, that's the kind of the way it is.

974
01:03:19,000 --> 01:03:20,000
The husband is ahead of the housing.

975
01:03:20,000 --> 01:03:23,000
They don't get upset about that, okay?

976
01:03:23,000 --> 01:03:28,000
And I think that's one of the things that really was very helpful on that.

977
01:03:28,000 --> 01:03:38,000
But we're now in May of 1960.

978
01:03:38,000 --> 01:03:46,000
So I was invited to come and speak to the state NAACP.

979
01:03:46,000 --> 01:03:51,000
And so when I spoke to them, I announced that we were going to march on May 17th

980
01:03:51,000 --> 01:04:00,000
to the Capitol to commemorate the Brown decision that had been made six years earlier on May 17th, 1954.

981
01:04:00,000 --> 01:04:06,000
I did not know that that was a report of that from the LA Constitution, Jalus.

982
01:04:06,000 --> 01:04:08,000
The following morning, it was headlines.

983
01:04:08,000 --> 01:04:12,000
The student leader announces massive march on the Capitol.

984
01:04:12,000 --> 01:04:14,000
The town went wild.

985
01:04:14,000 --> 01:04:17,000
Mind you now, they were still buzzing from the appeal of human rights,

986
01:04:17,000 --> 01:04:19,000
and all of us going to jail and all that kind of stuff.

987
01:04:19,000 --> 01:04:22,000
So they knew something was happening.

988
01:04:22,000 --> 01:04:31,000
Well, a government event of a called out the State Patrol.

989
01:04:31,000 --> 01:04:37,000
They surrounded the Capitol, almost armed with Billy Clubs and dogs,

990
01:04:37,000 --> 01:04:42,000
to keep us from coming down to the Capitol.

991
01:04:42,000 --> 01:04:55,000
So I had asked the students to meet me in front of the library that morning at 10 o'clock

992
01:04:55,000 --> 01:05:00,000
and they did thousands of them.

993
01:05:00,000 --> 01:05:09,000
So before we marched off, Ms. Hill, the same lady, I see her coming.

994
01:05:09,000 --> 01:05:15,000
I knew May's wasn't a senior.

995
01:05:15,000 --> 01:05:19,000
And so I told John Mack, who was my coach,

996
01:05:19,000 --> 01:05:24,000
and to keep them busy while I go see what Dr. May's wants.

997
01:05:24,000 --> 01:05:27,000
And so I went up there and so on.

998
01:05:27,000 --> 01:05:33,000
When I got there, it was May's and his wife, Miss Sadie May's.

999
01:05:33,000 --> 01:05:37,000
So May said that he had just spoken to Herbert Jenkins,

1000
01:05:37,000 --> 01:05:43,000
and that the ball of the State Troopers were down there with the Billy Clubs,

1001
01:05:43,000 --> 01:05:46,000
and what had even their whites who were gathered around.

1002
01:05:46,000 --> 01:05:51,000
And it looked like it's going to be a big mob mess down there.

1003
01:05:51,000 --> 01:05:55,000
And Jenkins emphasized that his jurisdiction ends at the Capitol.

1004
01:05:55,000 --> 01:05:59,000
He's not in charge of those State Troopers. The governor is.

1005
01:05:59,000 --> 01:06:04,000
So he couldn't protect us.

1006
01:06:04,000 --> 01:06:11,000
I don't think this is a matter of because you can't have a thought issue in the warning.

1007
01:06:11,000 --> 01:06:16,000
Asked me to not ask him, don't come because you might get hurt today.

1008
01:06:16,000 --> 01:06:19,000
So is he confirmed about the written person?

1009
01:06:19,000 --> 01:06:25,000
I think that Jenkins was a part of, he was the legal,

1010
01:06:25,000 --> 01:06:30,000
he was the police arm of the power structure in Atlanta.

1011
01:06:30,000 --> 01:06:34,000
Atlanta has a reputation of being the city to visit a hate.

1012
01:06:34,000 --> 01:06:38,000
It would not have been good for business if some students got beaten up in Atlanta.

1013
01:06:38,000 --> 01:06:41,000
So they lose some money. That's all it was about.

1014
01:06:41,000 --> 01:06:45,000
It's not about love for the students. It's about love for money.

1015
01:06:45,000 --> 01:06:49,000
So Dr. May's asked me not to go.

1016
01:06:49,000 --> 01:06:53,000
They got to give these people credit. They never ordered me to do anything.

1017
01:06:53,000 --> 01:06:56,000
They would let me know how they felt.

1018
01:06:56,000 --> 01:06:58,000
And so, and they gave me a chance to respond.

1019
01:06:58,000 --> 01:07:03,000
And so when he gave me all the reasons why we shouldn't do it

1020
01:07:03,000 --> 01:07:05,000
because of the risk of danger.

1021
01:07:05,000 --> 01:07:13,000
I said, with Dr. May's, let me take you back to a speech you made when I was sophomore.

1022
01:07:13,000 --> 01:07:18,000
I said, your speech was entitled, never sacrifice a principle for peace.

1023
01:07:18,000 --> 01:07:22,000
Do you remember that? He said, yes.

1024
01:07:22,000 --> 01:07:31,000
I said, you ask a million to sacrifice this principle of indesegregation

1025
01:07:31,000 --> 01:07:34,000
because I might get killed.

1026
01:07:34,000 --> 01:07:40,000
Therefore, in order to have peace, I got to leave alone.

1027
01:07:40,000 --> 01:07:44,000
He said, Mr. King, where are you going to end up?

1028
01:07:44,000 --> 01:07:47,000
I said, we should be doctors church.

1029
01:07:47,000 --> 01:07:51,000
He said, say that I will be there. That was the end of it.

1030
01:07:51,000 --> 01:07:56,000
So I went back to speak to these students and I did not know that May's followed me

1031
01:07:56,000 --> 01:08:00,000
until I read his book recently, born to rebel.

1032
01:08:00,000 --> 01:08:03,000
I happened to be reading the book.

1033
01:08:03,000 --> 01:08:05,000
And I went to that, and I got to that section.

1034
01:08:05,000 --> 01:08:09,000
He had followed me back.

1035
01:08:09,000 --> 01:08:17,000
And he heard me tell the students, which he described in his book,

1036
01:08:17,000 --> 01:08:23,000
that there were people downtown, one of the hurtest.

1037
01:08:23,000 --> 01:08:27,000
And this is a nonviolent movement.

1038
01:08:27,000 --> 01:08:30,000
If you cannot take the blows, don't go.

1039
01:08:30,000 --> 01:08:34,000
If you cannot afford to be spat on, don't go.

1040
01:08:34,000 --> 01:08:41,000
And I went through an alliteration of things that we only want people who are willing to be nonviolent as a tactic.

1041
01:08:41,000 --> 01:08:45,000
I'm not asking you to be nonviolent in your life, just as a tactic.

1042
01:08:45,000 --> 01:08:53,000
And when I finished my speech, not one of those 3000 plus kids said that they wanted to back out.

1043
01:08:53,000 --> 01:08:59,000
And May's describes that in his book that I didn't even know he had followed me down there until I read his book.

1044
01:08:59,000 --> 01:09:10,000
But he said in his book, he knew then that I had matured with the way he put it.

1045
01:09:10,000 --> 01:09:13,000
So what is he suggesting?

1046
01:09:13,000 --> 01:09:22,000
Well, I think before then, May's probably thought I was precipitous.

1047
01:09:22,000 --> 01:09:28,000
I had considered all the factors involved, the harm that might come to the students.

1048
01:09:28,000 --> 01:09:32,000
I think it was only at that point that he realized that I was very serious about this.

1049
01:09:32,000 --> 01:09:35,000
And I had a lot of folks behind me.

1050
01:09:35,000 --> 01:09:42,000
Now, I tell you, Dr. Emilye Crosby, if I did not have thousands of students backing me, I couldn't have done it.

1051
01:09:42,000 --> 01:09:51,000
See, because I don't care how good your cause is if you don't have any followers, you just listen to this, you just listen to Dixie.

1052
01:09:51,000 --> 01:09:58,000
But anyway, we went down there on May 17th that day and we marched down and there were a lot of pictures around about that.

1053
01:09:58,000 --> 01:10:11,000
So Herbert Jenkins, our floor mentioned, got out of his patrol car and started walking with me at the corner of Mitchell Street.

1054
01:10:11,000 --> 01:10:19,000
And so the two of us just walking along and he said, this is going to be Daniel's at the Capitol.

1055
01:10:19,000 --> 01:10:23,000
I said, yes, I know Dr. May's told me you are tall.

1056
01:10:23,000 --> 01:10:26,000
He said, well, I think you are not to do this.

1057
01:10:26,000 --> 01:10:30,000
I said, well, Chief, keep talking to me.

1058
01:10:30,000 --> 01:10:34,000
I said, but I think we have to do it.

1059
01:10:34,000 --> 01:10:47,000
So we walked up until we got to Spring Street and Mitchell, which is where the new post office, the new Russell Building is now.

1060
01:10:47,000 --> 01:11:03,000
So I said, Chief, if you give me a direct order as a Chief Law enforcement officer in the city at Peace Street Street, no, no, no, I'm sorry, Whitehall Street, which is now Peace Street Street.

1061
01:11:03,000 --> 01:11:09,000
I will turn. I said, I'm not trying to get anybody hurt.

1062
01:11:09,000 --> 01:11:12,000
I said, we are, we are making a point.

1063
01:11:12,000 --> 01:11:15,000
He said, okay, I'll do that.

1064
01:11:15,000 --> 01:11:20,000
But let me tell you what was my thinking.

1065
01:11:20,000 --> 01:11:27,000
Look at the environment. The Chamber of Commerce was a guestist. The White Community was a guestist.

1066
01:11:27,000 --> 01:11:33,000
Carlos Presidents was scared. A lot of parents were scared.

1067
01:11:33,000 --> 01:11:43,000
I said that if one student gets killed, then I'm planning to the arms of the enemies of what we're trying to do.

1068
01:11:43,000 --> 01:11:51,000
I said, it is very clear now that they've never had this number of students to march on anything in this town.

1069
01:11:51,000 --> 01:12:00,000
So I felt that I had made my point. Now I know it's a little bit conservative, but I decided to err on the side of conservatism in order to save the movement.

1070
01:12:00,000 --> 01:12:12,000
Because I felt that if one person got beaten up by a Billy Club, there would be forces that would be arguing to shut me down.

1071
01:12:12,000 --> 01:12:19,000
And so I followed his orders after I gave him the suggestion.

1072
01:12:19,000 --> 01:12:33,000
It was, it was hell. But then as fate would have it, we had so many people marching until about the last 200, they got lost.

1073
01:12:33,000 --> 01:12:36,000
And so they went on by the Capitol.

1074
01:12:36,000 --> 01:12:46,000
And when they got there, I learned from the leader of that part, Charles A. Black, that they, they, it was awful.

1075
01:12:46,000 --> 01:12:55,000
They didn't beat anybody, but they, but they were heckled by all the white bystanders and the state troopers.

1076
01:12:55,000 --> 01:13:14,000
It was a very menacing thing. But I saw something else about the crossbearing. When I looked at all this stuff lately, when you look at one of the photographs taken from the Capitol of that church across the street,

1077
01:13:14,000 --> 01:13:25,000
and all the folks that were out there, there were a number of African-American, young African-American men who were not students.

1078
01:13:25,000 --> 01:13:32,000
And I looked at that, I said, wait a minute. What's up here?

1079
01:13:32,000 --> 01:13:52,000
I can't prove this because folks are dead now. But that may have been a black vigilante group in Atlanta that could have very easily stepped into the fray if there was any kind of confrontation of a racial nature.

1080
01:13:52,000 --> 01:14:00,000
I was shocked to see them. And I come back to that later on because I had another chance to see something similar to that, okay?

1081
01:14:00,000 --> 01:14:10,000
Yeah. That may very well have been, if you want to put a pin right there, and I will just flash to tell you why I'm connected, I'm connected to them all.

1082
01:14:10,000 --> 01:14:26,000
So I started a boycott of this food stores changed right after that. And one of the stores that we went to was one place called Man Brothers, over in West End, Atlanta.

1083
01:14:26,000 --> 01:14:35,000
All the grocery stores hire Blacks as janitors and maids and stock clerks, but never as cashiers or managers or assistant managers.

1084
01:14:35,000 --> 01:14:44,000
Even though the business was 100% black, everybody was white who was in charge. So we pulled this boycott off over there.

1085
01:14:45,000 --> 01:15:00,000
And it was a high-wide act. So the newspaper in the West End had this front page editorial that sat at it before I came over there.

1086
01:15:00,000 --> 01:15:14,000
Because I announced that I was coming, all of us were coming. And read that they compared me to Hitler and that I was coming over there to change things.

1087
01:15:14,000 --> 01:15:20,000
When I got over there that Saturday, it was Charles A. Black, Frank Holloway and me.

1088
01:15:21,000 --> 01:15:27,000
And we were about 300 whites across the street, heckling us.

1089
01:15:27,000 --> 01:15:39,000
There was a white guy, about 57, who was there by us with his hand in his pocket. And we put Mays up and down with our picket sign and we would have you.

1090
01:15:40,000 --> 01:15:52,000
All of a sudden this white guy lunged at me and doused an acid like substance on me that burned like he wouldn't believe.

1091
01:15:52,000 --> 01:16:05,000
I mean, just burned my skin, my clothes, my shirt was destroyed. And I couldn't see terrible odor. Even the impacted two guys, even the impacted Frank Holloway and Charles, who were behind me.

1092
01:16:06,000 --> 01:16:22,000
So they rushed me to the hospital and I won't get in the honor of that except that. Well, I want you to set the stations and they wouldn't, the first service station would not let me get in the water but to leave. And then I, the second one did, allow me to do that.

1093
01:16:22,000 --> 01:16:30,000
Well, I learned later on that day that it was on the news.

1094
01:16:30,000 --> 01:16:40,000
And the pool hall was not modern, but it was honestly been a black pool hall, emptied of all the men when it came over.

1095
01:16:40,000 --> 01:16:54,000
They ran the West end to see what was going on. And I think Atlanta was very close to having a racial conflagration during that period of time.

1096
01:16:54,000 --> 01:17:04,000
But I think that cooler heads prevailed and they were willing to allow these students try to work this out.

1097
01:17:04,000 --> 01:17:14,000
But I think that there was possibly that potential for Birmingham kind of violence here, but it would have been quite versus blacks like you wouldn't believe.

1098
01:17:14,000 --> 01:17:16,000
Okay. That's just.

1099
01:17:16,000 --> 01:17:32,000
You think that you think that you could go through some of the names and say that and the way that you think they had a chance of, you were 13,000 in total, I part of those.

1100
01:17:32,000 --> 01:17:41,000
I'm not sure it was organized, but I would go with the latter point that you made. I don't know if anybody talking to them because it just don't know me.

1101
01:17:41,000 --> 01:17:55,000
I knew about the pool hall empty, but I didn't, but I had not seen those pictures of those fellows that were down there because it was an all white mop down there.

1102
01:17:55,000 --> 01:18:07,000
And I was saying in the middle, it's all white mop. What are these young black guys? Black maybe 18 to 25, hovering around back there in the background just spectators.

1103
01:18:07,000 --> 01:18:09,000
Let me, what's that all about?

1104
01:18:09,000 --> 01:18:11,000
Okay.

1105
01:18:13,000 --> 01:18:15,000
Where do you want me to go next?

1106
01:18:15,000 --> 01:18:26,000
Well, you mentioned before you went on that, you were on that scene talking to students about you know, you know, the parents were gone by.

1107
01:18:26,000 --> 01:18:28,000
And I'm going to take it very naturally.

1108
01:18:28,000 --> 01:18:31,000
They have a little sense of workshop and other places.

1109
01:18:31,000 --> 01:18:35,000
They do, you know, don't hit back kind of.

1110
01:18:35,000 --> 01:18:37,000
It's a very different approach.

1111
01:18:37,000 --> 01:18:38,000
Did you have any kind of training?

1112
01:18:38,000 --> 01:18:42,000
Or was it simply at any point in the process?

1113
01:18:42,000 --> 01:18:44,000
No, we did not.

1114
01:18:47,000 --> 01:18:55,000
Our panel, our committee, took the view that non-violent should be a tactic.

1115
01:18:55,000 --> 01:18:57,000
Not a way of life.

1116
01:18:57,000 --> 01:19:03,000
And therefore, that was a risk of us to go through all these.

1117
01:19:03,000 --> 01:19:09,000
Now, I don't know what happened after I left, but I doubt we were in a series of anyone actually ran into workshop.

1118
01:19:09,000 --> 01:19:13,000
Nashville was known for having done that.

1119
01:19:13,000 --> 01:19:20,000
And I can't really speak to whether that's more effective than just people adopting a tactic to be understood here.

1120
01:19:20,000 --> 01:19:24,000
And I know that many people have not been, but I know that there are also,

1121
01:19:24,000 --> 01:19:30,000
like not, and I don't even know a lot, and I know that the mix of some of those have workshop.

1122
01:19:30,000 --> 01:19:37,000
Just on, you know, so people have some factors to not have a bonding.

1123
01:19:37,000 --> 01:19:39,000
But it wasn't necessarily a thought factor.

1124
01:19:39,000 --> 01:19:41,000
It was still a very practical thing.

1125
01:19:41,000 --> 01:19:44,000
You know, it was a very few way to make it right.

1126
01:19:44,000 --> 01:19:45,000
Yeah.

1127
01:19:45,000 --> 01:19:49,000
But I think a lot of people also know that it was a good way to get that.

1128
01:19:49,000 --> 01:19:50,000
Yeah.

1129
01:19:50,000 --> 01:19:55,000
Let me try to rush through a lot of what I've written.

1130
01:19:55,000 --> 01:19:57,000
I've really covered some of this.

1131
01:19:57,000 --> 01:20:00,000
Let me try to rush through the Atlanta.

1132
01:20:00,000 --> 01:20:02,000
Let me talk about some institutions.

1133
01:20:02,000 --> 01:20:04,000
The Atlanta Daily World.

1134
01:20:04,000 --> 01:20:10,000
The oldest, it was the oldest contingencies running daily after the American newspaper in the country.

1135
01:20:10,000 --> 01:20:14,000
Possibly in the world, really.

1136
01:20:14,000 --> 01:20:20,000
They were an ultra-prod opposed to the movement, and what we were trying to do.

1137
01:20:20,000 --> 01:20:32,000
So, Julian was basically our arm, and I had hired Julian to that summer to write the publication

1138
01:20:32,000 --> 01:20:34,000
called the Student Movement in You.

1139
01:20:34,000 --> 01:20:36,000
We used the summer of 1960.

1140
01:20:36,000 --> 01:20:37,000
See, okay.

1141
01:20:37,000 --> 01:20:39,000
May 17 was a big rally.

1142
01:20:39,000 --> 01:20:42,000
Then it's exam time.

1143
01:20:42,000 --> 01:20:43,000
Then people are gone.

1144
01:20:43,000 --> 01:20:47,000
So, we had to organize for the fall, the fall campaign.

1145
01:20:47,000 --> 01:20:59,000
We had to also organize a boycott because we determined that we needed to boycott downtown

1146
01:20:59,000 --> 01:21:04,000
at Leningrad and automate them come to an agreement to integrate.

1147
01:21:04,000 --> 01:21:12,000
And we chose Richard's department store as the kingpin, all downtown but Richard's for sure.

1148
01:21:12,000 --> 01:21:20,000
In order to do that then, we had to battle with the old line black leadership who felt that Richard's was a great store, even though they were segregation,

1149
01:21:20,000 --> 01:21:23,000
safe segregated.

1150
01:21:23,000 --> 01:21:25,000
But how did you get around that?

1151
01:21:25,000 --> 01:21:34,000
Nine percent of African Americans in this town at that time were making a small amount of money.

1152
01:21:34,000 --> 01:21:39,000
That 10 percent were teachers and doctors and would have you.

1153
01:21:39,000 --> 01:21:46,000
But the bulk of the GNP was with the low income, $5 a day in coffee at people.

1154
01:21:46,000 --> 01:21:55,000
So, we needed to then organize around our strength and the strength was in the numbers.

1155
01:21:55,000 --> 01:21:59,000
And I remember when I was, I took economics with Dr. E.V. Williams.

1156
01:21:59,000 --> 01:22:06,000
I used to say that he'd much rather have the fast dime than the slow dollar.

1157
01:22:06,000 --> 01:22:09,000
Or he said that, hold up more dimes than their dollars.

1158
01:22:09,000 --> 01:22:12,000
And there are a lot of folks who have dimes.

1159
01:22:12,000 --> 01:22:27,000
And I used that along with another economics major named Dr. Hugo Schala, who taught me by John Foster Dulles' policy about the Domino Theory.

1160
01:22:28,000 --> 01:22:40,000
The communists felt that in the Pacific Basin, in fall, career falls, the rest of the basin will fall.

1161
01:22:40,000 --> 01:22:43,000
And it all will be communists all the way over.

1162
01:22:43,000 --> 01:22:45,000
Like Domino's, they fall in line.

1163
01:22:45,000 --> 01:22:50,000
And so I took the position that Richard's department store was like a major domino.

1164
01:22:50,000 --> 01:22:53,000
If we could knock down that domino piece, the rest will fall.

1165
01:22:53,000 --> 01:22:58,000
Because it was the largest store in the southeast.

1166
01:22:58,000 --> 01:22:59,000
So we took them all.

1167
01:22:59,000 --> 01:23:07,000
I went down there in June of 1960 for a meeting with, I sat down and I'm sorry, I sat in.

1168
01:23:07,000 --> 01:23:08,000
I took books down.

1169
01:23:08,000 --> 01:23:14,000
I took Dr. Zinn from Spelman, his daughter and his wife, myself.

1170
01:23:14,000 --> 01:23:18,000
I think Carolyn Long, down there to the Magnolia Room.

1171
01:23:19,000 --> 01:23:24,000
So they, of course, they closed the Magnolia Room when we got there.

1172
01:23:24,000 --> 01:23:30,000
And then Herbert Jenkins, this guy, took me down to jail.

1173
01:23:30,000 --> 01:23:39,000
Not to be arrested, but to have a conference meeting with Richard Rich in his office, Herbert Jenkins' office.

1174
01:23:39,000 --> 01:23:42,000
So when I got there, Richard Rich read as a beat.

1175
01:23:42,000 --> 01:23:47,000
And he talked about how good he had been for Negro citizens.

1176
01:23:48,000 --> 01:23:53,000
And he mentioned how he had supported the AU Center.

1177
01:23:53,000 --> 01:24:03,000
And he was the first one to ever put Mr. and Mrs. On the names of his customers when they set bills out.

1178
01:24:03,000 --> 01:24:08,000
The first one to give him charge plates, so forth and so on.

1179
01:24:08,000 --> 01:24:13,000
And you need to go take your, your student back to class.

1180
01:24:13,000 --> 01:24:18,000
And I gave him similar speech, you know, no, no, we have to, you have to change.

1181
01:24:18,000 --> 01:24:32,000
So Richard Rich said to me, I'm paraphrasing, if you bring your black ass down there again, I'm going to lock you up until the keys away, basically.

1182
01:24:32,000 --> 01:24:41,000
And I said, Mr. Rich, I will be back in the fall when I come back and bring thousands with me.

1183
01:24:41,000 --> 01:24:48,000
He turned redder and he told Herbert Jenkins, I'm through and he got up and walked out.

1184
01:24:48,000 --> 01:24:55,000
And so they took me back to my office down in Auburn Avenue, they'd teach people dead.

1185
01:24:55,000 --> 01:25:04,000
We're now riding this dude movement in you, Mr. Skywones Atlanta Daily World is constantly editorializing against the movement.

1186
01:25:04,000 --> 01:25:10,000
So we put out 20,000 leaflets per Sunday.

1187
01:25:10,000 --> 01:25:15,000
Through the churches we'll have you. Building the movement.

1188
01:25:15,000 --> 01:25:29,000
And one day in June 1960, in Wauksis, man that I thought was white in my office.

1189
01:25:29,000 --> 01:25:38,000
And I was a little edgy tall six foot three, six foot wide guy who had gotten all the way back to my office.

1190
01:25:38,000 --> 01:25:41,000
I didn't know if he was going to kill me or what, you know.

1191
01:25:41,000 --> 01:25:44,000
So I guess I'm up to look at apprehensive.

1192
01:25:44,000 --> 01:25:51,000
He sat down and he had the Atlanta Daily World in his hands and he said, my name is M. Kasuth Hill.

1193
01:25:51,000 --> 01:25:54,000
He said, oh, you're learning King, I suggest.

1194
01:25:54,000 --> 01:25:57,000
He said, I own Hill office supplies.

1195
01:25:57,000 --> 01:26:01,000
When he said that, I knew he had a good black guy, but he looked as white as anybody.

1196
01:26:01,000 --> 01:26:07,000
So I kind of, he said, this is a shame what this man is doing.

1197
01:26:07,000 --> 01:26:12,000
He said, now he's doing this because he wants to fight advertising.

1198
01:26:12,000 --> 01:26:18,000
And he's selling out the cause of human dignity.

1199
01:26:18,000 --> 01:26:24,000
He said, I own the rights to use the name get Atlanta in choir.

1200
01:26:24,000 --> 01:26:27,000
He said, I've always wanted to start a newspaper.

1201
01:26:27,000 --> 01:26:30,000
He said, I've got an attitude. His name is William Strong.

1202
01:26:30,000 --> 01:26:32,000
But I don't have any writers.

1203
01:26:32,000 --> 01:26:35,000
He said, if you're getting help me get people to hell with circulation,

1204
01:26:35,000 --> 01:26:38,000
he said, I will start it because I have an offset press.

1205
01:26:38,000 --> 01:26:43,000
So the two of us came together and we agreed that I will stop the student movement in you.

1206
01:26:43,000 --> 01:26:48,000
Have Julian go in right along with John Gibson and James Gibson and his brother and others.

1207
01:26:48,000 --> 01:26:52,000
Form the underbelly for that paper.

1208
01:26:52,000 --> 01:26:58,000
And on the Fed of Press of July, and you can find that in 1960, you may want to see that first issue.

1209
01:26:58,000 --> 01:27:00,000
Oh, you have.

1210
01:27:00,000 --> 01:27:03,000
Okay, all right.

1211
01:27:03,000 --> 01:27:06,000
And it's still around.

1212
01:27:06,000 --> 01:27:12,000
But that was started by M. Kasuth Hill, myself and the students.

1213
01:27:12,000 --> 01:27:14,000
It was not the folks that you read about.

1214
01:27:14,000 --> 01:27:16,000
They came in later.

1215
01:27:16,000 --> 01:27:19,000
But it was Mr. Hill who has not been given his due.

1216
01:27:19,000 --> 01:27:21,000
But I'm going to give him his due.

1217
01:27:21,000 --> 01:27:22,000
Because the man did it.

1218
01:27:22,000 --> 01:27:23,000
We know what else we're doing.

1219
01:27:23,000 --> 01:27:25,000
M. Kasuth Hill, not Jesse Hill Jr.

1220
01:27:25,000 --> 01:27:27,000
M. Kasuth Hill.

1221
01:27:27,000 --> 01:27:30,000
Did you read any sense of that in the last month when I'm happy with the world?

1222
01:27:30,000 --> 01:27:32,000
Oh, no question about it.

1223
01:27:32,000 --> 01:27:35,000
How did you learn to do that?

1224
01:27:35,000 --> 01:27:44,000
Well, we went to a lot of things that were happening at the same time.

1225
01:27:44,000 --> 01:27:53,000
We went to colonial stores and AMP stores right after that march.

1226
01:27:53,000 --> 01:27:58,000
And asked for these cashiers would have you.

1227
01:27:59,000 --> 01:28:03,000
I got a telephone call from Mr. Scott.

1228
01:28:03,000 --> 01:28:08,000
Telling me, C.A. Scott telling me, asking what I come down to seeing.

1229
01:28:08,000 --> 01:28:11,000
I saw what down to seeing.

1230
01:28:11,000 --> 01:28:17,000
And he proceeded to tell me that he's going to lose a $9,000 ad.

1231
01:28:17,000 --> 01:28:24,000
Or with the colonial stores if I didn't stop picketing.

1232
01:28:24,000 --> 01:28:27,000
And so Mr. Scott was spitting all over me.

1233
01:28:27,000 --> 01:28:30,000
Have you seen those folks who talked to you and your man in this,

1234
01:28:30,000 --> 01:28:31,000
that's not spitting well.

1235
01:28:31,000 --> 01:28:33,000
He was spitting all over me.

1236
01:28:33,000 --> 01:28:34,000
And so I'm just here listening to him.

1237
01:28:34,000 --> 01:28:36,000
Be that by me.

1238
01:28:36,000 --> 01:28:46,000
So I said, Mr. Scott, you know, in every revolution, some people get hurt.

1239
01:28:46,000 --> 01:28:50,000
But you don't call out the revolution because somebody might get hurt.

1240
01:28:50,000 --> 01:28:51,000
I said, you know what?

1241
01:28:51,000 --> 01:28:53,000
This is your time to get hurt.

1242
01:28:53,000 --> 01:28:55,000
I'm not going to do it.

1243
01:28:55,000 --> 01:28:57,000
He cursed me out and I left with the bottom line.

1244
01:28:57,000 --> 01:28:58,000
He didn't.

1245
01:28:58,000 --> 01:29:00,000
He was just brave, hate me.

1246
01:29:00,000 --> 01:29:05,000
And I guess I'm sure that Mr. Hill started the newspaper later.

1247
01:29:05,000 --> 01:29:06,000
That really got him.

1248
01:29:06,000 --> 01:29:10,000
Okay, because we were able to get them, they real stayed,

1249
01:29:10,000 --> 01:29:12,000
the black real stayed people.

1250
01:29:12,000 --> 01:29:16,000
We got them to take the ads out of Mr. Scott's paper and put them in the air.

1251
01:29:16,000 --> 01:29:19,000
So he really upset me, I guess.

1252
01:29:19,000 --> 01:29:25,000
He was upset with me.

1253
01:29:25,000 --> 01:29:28,000
But I think we, he never changed.

1254
01:29:28,000 --> 01:29:31,000
He was always like that to his death.

1255
01:29:31,000 --> 01:29:34,000
But I think we ripped his behind badly.

1256
01:29:34,000 --> 01:29:35,000
You know.

1257
01:29:35,000 --> 01:29:36,000
You can do it.

1258
01:29:36,000 --> 01:29:39,000
Can you stand with your first name?

1259
01:29:39,000 --> 01:29:41,000
Capital K.

1260
01:29:41,000 --> 01:29:46,000
All US-S-E-T-T-W.

1261
01:29:46,000 --> 01:29:47,000
It is.

1262
01:29:47,000 --> 01:29:49,000
Kassuth.

1263
01:29:49,000 --> 01:29:53,000
He was the son of the first African American doctor in this time.

1264
01:29:53,000 --> 01:30:02,000
And his wife was ginger Hill, who was the head,

1265
01:30:02,000 --> 01:30:08,000
she succeeded Whitney Young as the head of the Lowne University School of Social Work.

1266
01:30:08,000 --> 01:30:11,000
And I know that you look from college.

1267
01:30:11,000 --> 01:30:13,000
Well, it was a combination of me and Julia.

1268
01:30:13,000 --> 01:30:14,000
Oh, it is.

1269
01:30:14,000 --> 01:30:20,000
I wrote, I wrote, I had several, but I think Julia may have written about a third of them.

1270
01:30:20,000 --> 01:30:23,000
Because he was the deal.

1271
01:30:23,000 --> 01:30:29,000
Dr. Krosby, when you're trying to run a movement as big as this thing was,

1272
01:30:29,000 --> 01:30:31,000
you didn't have time.

1273
01:30:31,000 --> 01:30:32,000
You didn't have time?

1274
01:30:32,000 --> 01:30:33,000
I was a little busy.

1275
01:30:33,000 --> 01:30:37,000
Plus I worked on that at the post office, you know, on 6th, 6th, 3rd.

1276
01:30:37,000 --> 01:30:39,000
So I didn't have time to write to her.

1277
01:30:39,000 --> 01:30:42,000
I said, Julia, since I hired you, write my article,

1278
01:30:42,000 --> 01:30:43,000
I'm not able to write it.

1279
01:30:43,000 --> 01:30:44,000
And so he did that.

1280
01:30:44,000 --> 01:30:47,000
Oh, yeah, oh, yeah, yeah, yeah.

1281
01:30:47,000 --> 01:30:52,000
But that was, see, once we hired Mr. M. Carl Holman to come in and be the editor,

1282
01:30:52,000 --> 01:31:00,000
who took over who was real strong, we then tried to merge the message

1283
01:31:00,000 --> 01:31:04,000
between what's on the editorial page and the cartoon.

1284
01:31:04,000 --> 01:31:09,000
So if you didn't read the editorial, look at the cartoon and you still get the message.

1285
01:31:09,000 --> 01:31:14,000
And I've got to give you a man by the name of Maurice Pinington,

1286
01:31:14,000 --> 01:31:16,000
whom you may not have heard about.

1287
01:31:16,000 --> 01:31:23,000
An event that was one that I had forgotten that I had written.

1288
01:31:23,000 --> 01:31:29,000
When we went to jail, and we'll talk about that later on in October of 1960,

1289
01:31:29,000 --> 01:31:32,000
Martin King and I were in the same sale.

1290
01:31:32,000 --> 01:31:35,000
Because we were the leaders of the movement, you know, per se.

1291
01:31:35,000 --> 01:31:41,000
And I wrote an article, a letter from the Fulton County jail.

1292
01:31:41,000 --> 01:31:50,000
And I forgot that I had written the article until Dr.

1293
01:31:50,000 --> 01:31:55,000
the doctor up, who's a school, he has the School of Social Work at New York City, Georgia.

1294
01:31:55,000 --> 01:32:01,000
He wrote a biography of Don Hollowill.

1295
01:32:01,000 --> 01:32:04,000
And he had all these newspapers.

1296
01:32:04,000 --> 01:32:10,000
He said, let me send you a copy of what you said when you were in prison.

1297
01:32:10,000 --> 01:32:15,000
Yes, I did write that, but also Julian wrote some also.

1298
01:32:15,000 --> 01:32:18,000
Now, there's some who said Julian goes wrote all of them, that's not true.

1299
01:32:18,000 --> 01:32:22,000
Julian wrote some of them in that wrote some.

1300
01:32:22,000 --> 01:32:25,000
You said you were in the same company, but what about Maurice Pinington?

1301
01:32:25,000 --> 01:32:30,000
Yes, Maurice Pinington was, in my view, but for his race,

1302
01:32:30,000 --> 01:32:36,000
he would have been a claim as one of the greatest illustrators, all cartoonists in the country.

1303
01:32:36,000 --> 01:32:40,000
At the time that Herbert L. Block was so big, Pinington was just as good.

1304
01:32:40,000 --> 01:32:43,000
And I wish you could see some of his work.

1305
01:32:43,000 --> 01:32:50,000
We're going to have a big exhibit in Atlanta, 18th and 19th of October, at AU Library.

1306
01:32:50,000 --> 01:32:53,000
It'll be there for 30 days.

1307
01:32:53,000 --> 01:32:56,000
And it's going to be there for five years, for 30 days.

1308
01:32:56,000 --> 01:33:03,000
And we're going to show the, as many of the artifacts as we can pass with the pool together.

1309
01:33:03,000 --> 01:33:07,000
It's going to be a big show, and if you get a chance, it'll be good to come back down for that,

1310
01:33:07,000 --> 01:33:09,000
because it's going to be a big deal.

1311
01:33:09,000 --> 01:33:11,000
There's just a whole lot of stuff.

1312
01:33:11,000 --> 01:33:14,000
There's a whole lot of stuff that people have not seen.

1313
01:33:14,000 --> 01:33:20,000
We have 30, some cartoons from Mr. Pinington that just out of sight, that are going to be there.

1314
01:33:20,000 --> 01:33:25,000
Okay, plus he took 100 and some pictures of the movement that also will be down on the action movement.

1315
01:33:25,000 --> 01:33:27,000
Action stuff.

1316
01:33:27,000 --> 01:33:32,000
There's a wonderful picture from the movie.

1317
01:33:32,000 --> 01:33:35,000
Where did you see that?

1318
01:33:35,000 --> 01:33:38,000
That's not something we know that you are a college?

1319
01:33:38,000 --> 01:33:40,000
Okay, yes, yes, okay.

1320
01:33:40,000 --> 01:33:41,000
Well, that's...

1321
01:33:41,000 --> 01:33:45,000
Some of them were born on one of the anniversary committees.

1322
01:33:45,000 --> 01:33:46,000
Oh, yeah.

1323
01:33:46,000 --> 01:33:47,000
Yes, yes.

1324
01:33:47,000 --> 01:33:48,000
Yes, yes.

1325
01:33:48,000 --> 01:33:52,000
Well, we've just added to that exhibit.

1326
01:33:52,000 --> 01:33:55,000
There's a lot more down there now.

1327
01:33:55,000 --> 01:33:58,000
By October, you're going to have...

1328
01:33:58,000 --> 01:34:02,000
We'll have enough in there to go all the way around.

1329
01:34:02,000 --> 01:34:06,000
Because that stuff out there is just a matter of putting it all in one place.

1330
01:34:06,000 --> 01:34:09,000
What I saw wasn't actually on this play.

1331
01:34:09,000 --> 01:34:10,000
It was in boxes.

1332
01:34:10,000 --> 01:34:15,000
Yeah, well, we're going to take stuff out of the boxes, and we're going to add more stuff to those boxes.

1333
01:34:15,000 --> 01:34:20,000
Mrs. Pinington is waiting to sign a document that I've been prepared for her,

1334
01:34:20,000 --> 01:34:21,000
where she's going to launch.

1335
01:34:21,000 --> 01:34:25,000
She's going to lend us a lot of her stuff for five years.

1336
01:34:25,000 --> 01:34:28,000
I try to get it forever, but five years is fine.

1337
01:34:28,000 --> 01:34:29,000
That would have started.

1338
01:34:29,000 --> 01:34:31,000
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

1339
01:34:31,000 --> 01:34:34,000
So, I know there's a lot to talk about in the industry.

1340
01:34:34,000 --> 01:34:38,000
But can we take a deep one and talk about the findings, then?

1341
01:34:38,000 --> 01:34:39,000
Sure.

1342
01:34:39,000 --> 01:34:47,000
And, you know, I know the basic story, but I understand that you were present at the meeting in the hall.

1343
01:34:47,000 --> 01:34:50,000
Can you tell me what you remember?

1344
01:34:50,000 --> 01:34:52,000
Well, let me just say this to you.

1345
01:34:52,000 --> 01:34:57,000
And this has been written that many times, and you're going to get people who are going to be upset about it.

1346
01:34:57,000 --> 01:35:00,000
But you ought to ask that Reverend Dr. Otis Moss Jr,

1347
01:35:00,000 --> 01:35:07,000
whenever you talk to him, ask him about the founding of SNCC, because he was there.

1348
01:35:07,000 --> 01:35:12,000
Once we got going in that spring,

1349
01:35:13,000 --> 01:35:17,000
I recommended to our committee that I go to meet with Martin King

1350
01:35:17,000 --> 01:35:24,000
and see if I can get him to pull together a meeting of all of our student leaders to form some kind of a soft wide organization.

1351
01:35:24,000 --> 01:35:28,000
And Moss can attest to that.

1352
01:35:28,000 --> 01:35:32,000
He was in that meeting.

1353
01:35:32,000 --> 01:35:37,000
I called up Dr. King, and I already knew him, and so said that to the meeting,

1354
01:35:37,000 --> 01:35:41,000
and we went down there to see him.

1355
01:35:42,000 --> 01:35:51,000
And the meeting was Ella Baker, Dr. King and me, and to a couple of the students whose members are gotten kind of foggy,

1356
01:35:51,000 --> 01:35:55,000
but I'm not even getting all of that.

1357
01:35:55,000 --> 01:36:03,000
But I made the argument that the people that we were battling were highly organized.

1358
01:36:03,000 --> 01:36:10,000
And I pointed out that we were battling the system that,

1359
01:36:10,000 --> 01:36:16,000
from Maryland to Texas, they're on the same page.

1360
01:36:16,000 --> 01:36:21,000
And I cited the fact that when Virginia passed in, I trust passed laws.

1361
01:36:21,000 --> 01:36:24,000
Maryland quickly passed in Virginia.

1362
01:36:24,000 --> 01:36:30,000
I'm North Carolina, South Carolina, Georgia, all around, all around, all these days passed the same kind of law.

1363
01:36:30,000 --> 01:36:33,000
Almost word for word, like Attic today.

1364
01:36:33,000 --> 01:36:38,000
I said, so the people that we're fighting, they're organized.

1365
01:36:38,000 --> 01:36:45,000
And my point was that there is no known force that I've never heard of in the world,

1366
01:36:45,000 --> 01:36:50,000
where you had a revolution that was unorganized.

1367
01:36:50,000 --> 01:36:54,000
The people that you're battling organized, so you gotta get organized, it beat them.

1368
01:36:54,000 --> 01:36:59,000
I said, the only example to that Dr. King might be the French Revolution,

1369
01:36:59,000 --> 01:37:01,000
where he said the mass as well as that.

1370
01:37:01,000 --> 01:37:05,000
But when you look beyond the French Revolution, look into the intercourse,

1371
01:37:05,000 --> 01:37:09,000
look at the instance that was the middle class there,

1372
01:37:09,000 --> 01:37:11,000
that was pushing them.

1373
01:37:11,000 --> 01:37:15,000
So Alabaca on the other hand, and this is contrary to what you read,

1374
01:37:15,000 --> 01:37:20,000
opposed organizing this way.

1375
01:37:20,000 --> 01:37:22,000
So it was a battle between her and me.

1376
01:37:22,000 --> 01:37:29,000
She said that we needed to allow the movement organization to kind of

1377
01:37:29,000 --> 01:37:35,000
She fell off from the grass roots and she used an Indian expression to,

1378
01:37:35,000 --> 01:37:38,000
what's it called, such a hot gruffa?

1379
01:37:38,000 --> 01:37:43,000
Yeah, she used that expression as the basis for her position.

1380
01:37:43,000 --> 01:37:48,000
Martin King said, he agreed with me and he gave, he said,

1381
01:37:48,000 --> 01:37:53,000
I'm going to put a 500 dollars and I want you to Ellen get a place

1382
01:37:53,000 --> 01:37:56,000
for us to call this conference over Easter weekend.

1383
01:37:56,000 --> 01:38:04,000
Of course, she finished show and so she got show to host it.

1384
01:38:04,000 --> 01:38:08,000
We were there.

1385
01:38:08,000 --> 01:38:16,000
For whatever the reason, Ellen and Martin party company doing that period of time.

1386
01:38:16,000 --> 01:38:21,000
So by the time she got to the conference, she either was out the door,

1387
01:38:21,000 --> 01:38:24,000
or was about to go out the door.

1388
01:38:24,000 --> 01:38:28,000
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

1389
01:38:28,000 --> 01:38:32,000
My impression is that Miss Baker,

1390
01:38:32,000 --> 01:38:35,000
well, I'll put this one.

1391
01:38:35,000 --> 01:38:41,000
A lot of African American preachers are very showvinistic.

1392
01:38:41,000 --> 01:38:47,000
And Miss Baker, from their perspective, did not know her place.

1393
01:38:47,000 --> 01:38:52,000
And she was an outspoken person who would say what was on her mind.

1394
01:38:52,000 --> 01:38:55,000
And that always got in trouble with these preachers.

1395
01:38:55,000 --> 01:38:58,000
And I think that might have gotten in trouble with Martin King,

1396
01:38:58,000 --> 01:38:59,000
to be honest with you.

1397
01:38:59,000 --> 01:39:03,000
And if not him, some of his people around.

1398
01:39:03,000 --> 01:39:11,000
So we were there, Dr. Abbott Davis, who was the head of Atlanta Medical Society,

1399
01:39:11,000 --> 01:39:19,000
rented a brand new 1960 white Buick for us to go up there.

1400
01:39:19,000 --> 01:39:25,000
So six of us in the car who went from Atlanta to that conference.

1401
01:39:25,000 --> 01:39:28,000
And I think Johnny Parham, who was also part of our group,

1402
01:39:28,000 --> 01:39:32,000
flew in from some other place, but he was there too.

1403
01:39:32,000 --> 01:39:37,000
My recollection is that it was Julian, Ben Brown,

1404
01:39:37,000 --> 01:39:45,000
I think Marion Smith, Marian Wright Edelman.

1405
01:39:45,000 --> 01:39:51,000
And I believe it must have been Child of Frank Lyle, the other way LES I think.

1406
01:39:51,000 --> 01:39:55,000
He's a guy from some of you who went to Texas.

1407
01:39:55,000 --> 01:39:57,000
But anyway, we all were there.

1408
01:39:57,000 --> 01:40:01,000
And so Nick was formed, as you will know.

1409
01:40:01,000 --> 01:40:09,000
A lot of, it was good to sit 300 people roughly there, under the same umbrella.

1410
01:40:09,000 --> 01:40:14,000
Now there are those who claim that Dr. King wanted Nick to become a junior arm

1411
01:40:14,000 --> 01:40:17,000
of SCLC.

1412
01:40:17,000 --> 01:40:23,000
I don't want to doubt that he didn't, as far as that, but he never talked to me about that.

1413
01:40:23,000 --> 01:40:27,000
And I don't know anybody else that he talked to about that.

1414
01:40:27,000 --> 01:40:31,000
But there were those who felt that that's what he was trying to do.

1415
01:40:31,000 --> 01:40:32,000
They may have evidence.

1416
01:40:32,000 --> 01:40:34,000
I don't have the evidence.

1417
01:40:34,000 --> 01:40:40,000
Of course, I honestly believe Dr. Emilye Crosby, considering the man's charisma,

1418
01:40:41,000 --> 01:40:46,000
if King had wanted us to become a junior arm of SCLC, it would have happened.

1419
01:40:46,000 --> 01:40:56,000
I mean, there was nobody there who had the force of ouratory that could have overwritten King.

1420
01:40:56,000 --> 01:41:00,000
If he had wanted to do it, but I didn't see that happen at all.

1421
01:41:00,000 --> 01:41:05,000
I have a very small technical question, some details questions.

1422
01:41:06,000 --> 01:41:11,000
I know Marion Barry were in the first chair of the Temporary Coordinating Committee.

1423
01:41:11,000 --> 01:41:13,000
But I've seen different things.

1424
01:41:13,000 --> 01:41:15,000
Some people say that he was elected in April.

1425
01:41:15,000 --> 01:41:19,000
And some people say he was elected for some documents.

1426
01:41:19,000 --> 01:41:21,000
I mean, it's a variety of different kinds of doubts.

1427
01:41:21,000 --> 01:41:25,000
At the first May coordinating committee here in Atlanta.

1428
01:41:25,000 --> 01:41:27,000
Do you have a recollection of that?

1429
01:41:27,000 --> 01:41:28,000
Yeah.

1430
01:41:28,000 --> 01:41:31,000
Marion Barry.

1431
01:41:31,000 --> 01:41:34,000
Okay, that was a battle going on here.

1432
01:41:35,000 --> 01:41:42,000
My name got put up as the first chairman.

1433
01:41:42,000 --> 01:41:47,000
The folks of Nashville brought in a guy, Marion Barry.

1434
01:41:47,000 --> 01:41:49,000
That never heard of before as their candidate.

1435
01:41:49,000 --> 01:41:53,000
I thought it would have been Diane Nash, but it was Barry.

1436
01:41:53,000 --> 01:41:57,000
So you had this jock in going along.

1437
01:41:57,000 --> 01:42:03,000
So finally, a compromise was reached.

1438
01:42:03,000 --> 01:42:11,000
Less you'd like Barry as a temporary chairman and remove the headquarters to Atlanta.

1439
01:42:11,000 --> 01:42:16,000
And we paid the rent for the first several months.

1440
01:42:16,000 --> 01:42:18,000
And the records already showed that.

1441
01:42:18,000 --> 01:42:21,000
I mean, I've got the records on that, okay?

1442
01:42:21,000 --> 01:42:23,000
That office paid the rent.

1443
01:42:23,000 --> 01:42:29,000
I hadn't seen that, but I have seen some of the financial records that showed that the Atlanta group

1444
01:42:29,000 --> 01:42:32,000
was putting on the donate.

1445
01:42:32,000 --> 01:42:35,000
Right, right, but it was for the rent.

1446
01:42:35,000 --> 01:42:46,000
But my position was we need this organization to coordinate and would have you.

1447
01:42:46,000 --> 01:42:53,000
There are some people who have the view that if you didn't write it down then it didn't happen.

1448
01:42:53,000 --> 01:42:58,000
That's not really true, but haven't said that.

1449
01:42:58,000 --> 01:43:02,000
The move to Atlanta was the best thing that I think stick could have done.

1450
01:43:02,000 --> 01:43:05,000
I don't think they could have done it from Nashville, okay?

1451
01:43:05,000 --> 01:43:10,000
In retrospect, from an outside perspective, it seems like the logical move.

1452
01:43:10,000 --> 01:43:17,000
It was logical because Atlanta historically has been the citadel of intellectual thinking

1453
01:43:17,000 --> 01:43:22,000
and action in the Civil Rights Movement beginning really with WB Duboy.

1454
01:43:22,000 --> 01:43:30,000
And when he was there, you for 20-something years, and he had all those wonderful things that he did over there.

1455
01:43:30,000 --> 01:43:36,000
It's unfortunate that this town until recently has never recognized this man's genius.

1456
01:43:36,000 --> 01:43:41,000
It's been clock AU just put up a statute form, but that's been one of the things.

1457
01:43:41,000 --> 01:43:47,000
They name all these streets after people who have done nothing in this town or in this country.

1458
01:43:47,000 --> 01:43:54,000
But because they're part of a certain click that can get these things done, how about a guy like Duboy, who was a giant,

1459
01:43:54,000 --> 01:44:00,000
not just in the United States of America, but in the world.

1460
01:44:00,000 --> 01:44:06,000
It's an interesting town, I put it like that.

1461
01:44:06,000 --> 01:44:13,000
She should have been there.

1462
01:44:13,000 --> 01:44:20,000
Diane Nash, in my view, was the Nashville Movement.

1463
01:44:20,000 --> 01:44:23,000
And by that I mean this.

1464
01:44:23,000 --> 01:44:29,000
Others were there, but they weren't Diane Nash. Diane was articulate.

1465
01:44:29,000 --> 01:44:35,000
She's beautiful woman, very photogenic, very committed.

1466
01:44:35,000 --> 01:44:42,000
And very intelligent, and had a following.

1467
01:44:42,000 --> 01:44:48,000
I never did understand how, except maybe it was sexism.

1468
01:44:48,000 --> 01:44:59,000
I never understood how James Bevel, Marion Barry, and for that matter, John Lewis kind of leapfrogged over.

1469
01:44:59,000 --> 01:45:04,000
I never understood that because she was in fact the leader in Nashville.

1470
01:45:04,000 --> 01:45:06,000
It was Diane.

1471
01:45:06,000 --> 01:45:09,000
And the others were followers of hers.

1472
01:45:09,000 --> 01:45:17,000
Now James Lawson was going, well he was in the James Lawson, but he was an adult who was kind of working with the student.

1473
01:45:17,000 --> 01:45:18,000
But it was Diane.

1474
01:45:18,000 --> 01:45:27,000
So I never understood that to be honest with you, but she's a real unsung hero of the movement in Nashville, in my opinion.

1475
01:45:27,000 --> 01:45:30,000
Risk of life in order to make this thing happen.

1476
01:45:30,000 --> 01:45:40,000
I think some accounts, and I'm like, you know, again, you know, you know, a few of those snippets here and there, and you can see them, and I know there's a different kind of, some of it, there's some certain that they believe in some of these contradictory.

1477
01:45:40,000 --> 01:45:50,000
But you know, one, one account, and I think Marion, very serious, is that the expectation was that Diane Nash, that the Nashville Group wanted to put Nashville in the chair.

1478
01:45:50,000 --> 01:46:02,000
And they mentioned the competition with Atlanta, but that at some point, or some meeting she wasn't present, and he was, so he became kind of the person.

1479
01:46:02,000 --> 01:46:08,000
The consensus? Well that may have happened because they were having the meetings, you know, because we didn't know anything about that part of it.

1480
01:46:08,000 --> 01:46:14,000
I was just shocked though when they came back, when Barry's name was put forward, I was shocked about that.

1481
01:46:14,000 --> 01:46:17,000
Because she was the one who literally put them on the map up there.

1482
01:46:17,000 --> 01:46:22,000
Now was that at Shaw in April, or was that in the land in May?

1483
01:46:22,000 --> 01:46:33,000
Diane, well, we actually elected a temporary chairman in at Shaw, pending going to the next meeting.

1484
01:46:33,000 --> 01:46:42,000
But Barry, by being the temporary chairman, also being the chairman anyway, you know, if you ever get that first leg, yeah.

1485
01:46:42,000 --> 01:46:51,000
But I never understood what the Nashville folks were doing when they overlooked the lady who really brought them to the table.

1486
01:46:51,000 --> 01:46:55,000
So did you have a sense of her reputation? Oh yes.

1487
01:46:55,000 --> 01:47:07,000
Oh yes. Oh yes. Diane Nash was, in my view, Diane Nash was the most articulate advocate of the movement at that time.

1488
01:47:07,000 --> 01:47:12,000
And I never understood what was happening in Nashville, beyond it, just you. Except maybe sexism.

1489
01:47:12,000 --> 01:47:18,000
Did you have a sense of other leaders from other communities before that law in the United States?

1490
01:47:18,000 --> 01:47:24,000
Yeah, I had read about David Forbes, I guess his name, I had heard about him.

1491
01:47:24,000 --> 01:47:28,000
And I had heard about a guy named...

1492
01:47:28,000 --> 01:47:35,000
Forbes was that Shaw University.

1493
01:47:35,000 --> 01:47:40,000
Not even David Forbes. David Forbes, not Franklin, David Forbes. David Forbes.

1494
01:47:40,000 --> 01:47:53,000
I had heard about him, and I heard about Ed King, who came to Snick, who was put out of Kentucky State.

1495
01:47:53,000 --> 01:48:00,000
And I heard about a guy named Robinson, who led the movement down at Southern.

1496
01:48:00,000 --> 01:48:05,000
I forgot Robinson, why wasn't it, why didn't it go to the Marvel Robinson? Marvin Robinson, yes.

1497
01:48:05,000 --> 01:48:14,000
I heard about him. I heard about the two sisters down in Tallahassee.

1498
01:48:14,000 --> 01:48:17,000
Is it...

1499
01:48:17,000 --> 01:48:23,000
Yeah, the dad is a pastor. I had heard about them.

1500
01:48:23,000 --> 01:48:32,000
I had heard about Chuck McDo in Orange, Burst, South Carolina.

1501
01:48:32,000 --> 01:48:38,000
Who else?

1502
01:48:38,000 --> 01:48:45,000
The movement down in Savannah was being run by the NAACP. I had heard about Mr. Laws, but you told my students now.

1503
01:48:46,000 --> 01:48:57,000
I heard about the students being kicked out of Alabama State, but I didn't know any names until August when Bernard S. Lee came to join us in Atlanta.

1504
01:49:01,000 --> 01:49:06,000
Of course, you knew the names of the four kids from Greensboro, but I never met them.

1505
01:49:06,000 --> 01:49:12,000
In fact, you know what? I don't recall them, but not those boys with them. Were they there in the Ad Raleigh?

1506
01:49:12,000 --> 01:49:19,000
He's a player for school. He went to a school with a coordinating committee.

1507
01:49:19,000 --> 01:49:22,000
Oh, okay, okay.

1508
01:49:22,000 --> 01:49:27,000
Yeah, come to think of it.

1509
01:49:27,000 --> 01:49:39,000
Now, there was another young man, but I learned about him late on after Snick. I got started. That was Hank Thomas.

1510
01:49:39,000 --> 01:49:46,000
And another guy who went around Hank all the time, Reginald Robinson.

1511
01:49:46,000 --> 01:49:51,000
But I heard about them late on during the year.

1512
01:49:51,000 --> 01:49:55,000
How old did you get back to the other man?

1513
01:49:55,000 --> 01:49:59,000
When you came to the Ad Raleigh, you were born in the 18th century.

1514
01:49:59,000 --> 01:50:04,000
Not too many people who were known and well were able to describe him and grow old.

1515
01:50:04,000 --> 01:50:07,000
I was born in the 18th century.

1516
01:50:07,000 --> 01:50:14,000
Yeah, I have a picture of Ed King. Ed King.

1517
01:50:14,000 --> 01:50:17,000
Is that one of the demonstrations?

1518
01:50:17,000 --> 01:50:23,000
Yeah, Ed King is the first person to come in here to help us as a secretary.

1519
01:50:23,000 --> 01:50:27,000
The Ministry of Office was Jane Stembridge.

1520
01:50:27,000 --> 01:50:30,000
And the second person was Ed King.

1521
01:50:30,000 --> 01:50:35,000
A lot of folks who want to try to pretend like they don't know Ed King, but Ed King was here.

1522
01:50:35,000 --> 01:50:40,000
And he actually was running this office full-stick.

1523
01:50:40,000 --> 01:50:46,000
I don't know why people want to write him out, but by the way, he died in January of last year.

1524
01:50:46,000 --> 01:50:49,000
I've been trying to find him.

1525
01:50:49,000 --> 01:50:56,000
No, Ed King died in Montgomery and Prince George's County.

1526
01:50:56,000 --> 01:51:00,000
Yes, I can get you the newspaper stuff. I'll send it to you.

1527
01:51:00,000 --> 01:51:03,000
Ed King, I've been looking for the man.

1528
01:51:03,000 --> 01:51:11,000
And so finally one day here, I said, let me go find him at King because he never comes back to these reunion and would have you.

1529
01:51:11,000 --> 01:51:19,000
And I looked it up and sure enough he died in January of 2012 in Prince George's County.

1530
01:51:19,000 --> 01:51:24,000
And it is the same person. He was born in Virginia, which you probably know.

1531
01:51:24,000 --> 01:51:27,000
I'm not sure whether it's Ron Ork or what have you.

1532
01:51:27,000 --> 01:51:31,000
I know how he was expelled from Kentucky State. That's him.

1533
01:51:31,000 --> 01:51:36,000
I felt badly because I had one of the breachums several years ago, but didn't know how to find him.

1534
01:51:36,000 --> 01:51:40,000
I come to find out the man was less than 30 miles away from me.

1535
01:51:40,000 --> 01:51:43,000
But he just kind of dropped out of sight.

1536
01:51:43,000 --> 01:51:49,000
Yeah, I know you know back to school. You know, you know, high.

1537
01:51:49,000 --> 01:51:52,000
Or were before?

1538
01:51:52,000 --> 01:51:55,000
So can you describe him for me or his role?

1539
01:51:55,000 --> 01:52:05,000
Yeah, Ed King was. Ed King was very effective in being a coordinator at at SNCC.

1540
01:52:05,000 --> 01:52:08,000
He worked very closely with us in Atlanta movement.

1541
01:52:08,000 --> 01:52:13,000
And a person that was especially close to him was Marion Wilson.

1542
01:52:13,000 --> 01:52:16,000
They were very close.

1543
01:52:16,000 --> 01:52:24,000
Ed was an articulate speaker. He was courageous, well organized.

1544
01:52:24,000 --> 01:52:28,000
He did a job for SNCC at the time when we needed somebody.

1545
01:52:28,000 --> 01:52:31,000
And he's kind of unharrowed, be honest with you.

1546
01:52:31,000 --> 01:52:35,000
And there's another guy named Ed King who's a white guy, Mississippi.

1547
01:52:35,000 --> 01:52:41,000
And a lot of folks have refused those two, but there were two Ed Kings.

1548
01:52:41,000 --> 01:52:44,000
So I know there was a person.

1549
01:52:44,000 --> 01:52:46,000
A town.

1550
01:52:46,000 --> 01:52:52,000
I only knew there was a mile one and we got, you know, and we had all the way.

1551
01:52:52,000 --> 01:52:55,000
Well, let's go as far as we can.

1552
01:52:55,000 --> 01:52:58,000
Yeah, yeah.

1553
01:52:58,000 --> 01:53:01,000
Once you ask all you want to get all your questions in,

1554
01:53:01,000 --> 01:53:04,000
then I do my best to weave other stuff in as you ask questions.

1555
01:53:04,000 --> 01:53:07,000
Because I want to make sure that I answer all your stuff, okay?

1556
01:53:07,000 --> 01:53:11,000
Well, you know, some other people might be thinking about some of the big points.

1557
01:53:11,000 --> 01:53:18,000
So why don't you tell me, I know we talked to some of the boy called active women in summer 1960.

1558
01:53:18,000 --> 01:53:23,000
You know, you resume those big campaigns that Atlanta students and the fallers.

1559
01:53:23,000 --> 01:53:25,000
And I know you have those.

1560
01:53:25,000 --> 01:53:31,000
You know, the big events that might mean the change in some of the strategic decisions that will happen in spring.

1561
01:53:31,000 --> 01:53:35,000
I know that you want to talk about some of those things that you think are particularly significant,

1562
01:53:35,000 --> 01:53:39,000
that they are, I think, so that's the most important.

1563
01:53:39,000 --> 01:53:44,000
Well, we put the plan together.

1564
01:53:44,000 --> 01:53:49,000
Once we got the inquiry going on, we began to get people joining us.

1565
01:53:49,000 --> 01:53:55,000
We spoke all over town, trying to build up a grounds for the fall campaign.

1566
01:53:55,000 --> 01:53:57,000
And it was too prom.

1567
01:53:57,000 --> 01:54:01,000
Sittings are confident with boycotts, so forth and so on.

1568
01:54:01,000 --> 01:54:08,000
And by the way, I just found out here recently, Richard's lost $10 million during that period of time, that I just found out.

1569
01:54:08,000 --> 01:54:12,000
Somebody from the mountains who are involved, say, you all were looking at stock exchange?

1570
01:54:12,000 --> 01:54:18,000
Yes, we were. Yes, yes. Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes. Dr. Hugo Scala.

1571
01:54:18,000 --> 01:54:20,000
Yeah. And Dr. E.V. Williams. Yeah.

1572
01:54:20,000 --> 01:54:25,000
We watched them every, every Sunday. They stopped publishing after a while.

1573
01:54:25,000 --> 01:54:29,000
But anyway, where was I?

1574
01:54:29,000 --> 01:54:34,000
I was talking about the two-phone, the purchase.

1575
01:54:34,000 --> 01:54:40,000
Yes. Yes. So in September, the students were back.

1576
01:54:40,000 --> 01:54:43,000
We had the plans.

1577
01:54:43,000 --> 01:54:52,000
So I presented the summer work as part of the fall campaign.

1578
01:54:52,000 --> 01:54:54,000
He's what we want to do.

1579
01:54:54,000 --> 01:55:01,000
And I had to battle, believe it or not, with the AD King, Martin's younger brother, and Bernard S. Lee.

1580
01:55:01,000 --> 01:55:08,000
To try to get that approved, the issue was, do we wait till October the 19th?

1581
01:55:08,000 --> 01:55:11,000
Or do we go now?

1582
01:55:11,000 --> 01:55:16,000
And my point was, we want to time this with the Presidents of the election.

1583
01:55:16,000 --> 01:55:20,000
So they were even in the study. They wanted to go. They wanted to go.

1584
01:55:20,000 --> 01:55:23,000
They wanted to go now. Now, now, now. And so we said, no, miss.

1585
01:55:23,000 --> 01:55:27,000
And so I prevailed only because the Spelman folks backed me.

1586
01:55:27,000 --> 01:55:32,000
You know, they backed me. And we waited until October the 19th.

1587
01:55:32,000 --> 01:55:37,000
Now, my answer, I had Carl Martin King in August to tell him about

1588
01:55:37,000 --> 01:55:41,000
what we were going to do. And he agreed to come at that time.

1589
01:55:41,000 --> 01:55:50,000
And so her share of Sullivan, Herschelle Sullivan, came back from Paris in September.

1590
01:55:50,000 --> 01:55:58,000
And she became the cold chairman to take the place of the guy from AU, who they graduated, John Mac.

1591
01:55:58,000 --> 01:56:01,000
So she was, she led the Spelman delegation.

1592
01:56:01,000 --> 01:56:10,000
And I convinced her to back me on waiting until October the 19th.

1593
01:56:10,000 --> 01:56:17,000
So on the 18th, I said, her shell, give him a call.

1594
01:56:17,000 --> 01:56:22,000
Give Dr. King, I call him male, but give Dr. King a call and tell him to meet me on a bridge

1595
01:56:22,000 --> 01:56:30,000
at 10 in the morning. So she came back and she said, no, he said he can't go.

1596
01:56:30,000 --> 01:56:37,000
Oh, the riches, yeah, rich, at Riches Department store, on the second floor,

1597
01:56:37,000 --> 01:56:45,000
that was a cafeteria that separated, that was over the street between broad and for

1598
01:56:45,000 --> 01:56:50,000
safe. And it was like, yeah, you could sit in the cafeteria and you could look at the traffic

1599
01:56:50,000 --> 01:56:56,000
going up and down those streets. It separated the store from homes, which was on the left

1600
01:56:56,000 --> 01:57:06,000
side from the regular Riches facility. And so when she called him, he told her that he

1601
01:57:06,000 --> 01:57:17,000
couldn't go. And I said, but her shell talked to students here. Let me go talk to her.

1602
01:57:17,000 --> 01:57:23,000
Because I knew I had a relationship from 1945, you follow me? So I called him up and of course

1603
01:57:23,000 --> 01:57:28,000
on the phone was his daddy. Believe it or not, AD was on the phone for some reason,

1604
01:57:28,000 --> 01:57:33,000
instead of being out there, he was on the phone. Wyatt T. Walker was in the room.

1605
01:57:33,000 --> 01:57:41,000
Yeah, they're all there. And so he, in his very slow, different way, he said, I can't

1606
01:57:41,000 --> 01:57:47,000
go because I was arrested and I'm on probation from an arrest for bleeding Smith out in the

1607
01:57:47,000 --> 01:57:54,000
county. And if I get arrested, I've been advised that they probably revoke my parole,

1608
01:57:54,000 --> 01:58:04,000
not parole, but probation, probation. And so, and his dad, of course, he was bombastic,

1609
01:58:04,000 --> 01:58:12,000
you know, daddy came. Anyway, I ignored daddy came and other folks on the phone had just

1610
01:58:12,000 --> 01:58:24,000
talked to him. And I said, email, Atlanta's your hometown. You need to go with us. He had

1611
01:58:24,000 --> 01:58:29,000
never been the jail of a lot of Ontario before then. They would come and get him. I said,

1612
01:58:29,000 --> 01:58:37,000
but if you get arrested with us, it'll be international news. And I think that that's what the

1613
01:58:37,000 --> 01:58:48,000
movement needs. And I said, Martin Luther King Sr, do you remember a sermon that you preached

1614
01:58:48,000 --> 01:58:56,000
a few years ago called, you can't leave from the back. Got to leave from the front. I said,

1615
01:58:56,000 --> 01:59:03,000
well, email, you can't leave from the back. You got to leave from the front. That was designed

1616
01:59:03,000 --> 01:59:10,000
to silence his daddy, who was on my case by putting it back in his face. And they also

1617
01:59:10,000 --> 01:59:17,000
had a mail here that sermon too, because he was there. He said, they'll see, they call me LC.

1618
01:59:17,000 --> 01:59:28,000
He said, where should I come tomorrow? I said 10 o'clock on the bridge. He said, I'll be there. That's how that happened.

1619
01:59:28,000 --> 01:59:39,000
Well, I believe a talk to Harris Wofford, who's still alive, by the way. I was surprised that he was

1620
01:59:39,000 --> 01:59:47,000
still alive. I called him and left a message for him when I found he was still alive. And I got

1621
01:59:47,000 --> 01:59:55,000
a call back on my answer machine where he wanted to know if this is a lightning king who got me fired.

1622
01:59:55,000 --> 02:00:07,000
Oh, God. And so I called him back and I said, yes, yes, I did get you fired. And of course,

1623
02:00:07,000 --> 02:00:11,000
he told me later on about what happened between him and the kin of this and all that kind of stuff.

1624
02:00:11,000 --> 02:00:19,000
Of course, he spoke out of school when he did certain things. Anyway, having said that, when

1625
02:00:19,000 --> 02:00:28,000
the kin was arrested, it was like a firestorm that went all over the community, all of

1626
02:00:28,000 --> 02:00:35,000
the American, the black community. Now, African Americans have been voting except for Roosevelt for

1627
02:00:35,000 --> 02:00:50,000
Republicans since 1865, 1867, I guess. But when Kennedy interceded or his brother and interceded

1628
02:00:50,000 --> 02:00:58,000
and Kennedy got the credit for it, after he called Coretta Scott King, it switched the votes in a lot of different states.

1629
02:00:58,000 --> 02:01:04,000
You know, Illinois, Michigan, all over the place. There's been a difference in that. It was not the dead

1630
02:01:04,000 --> 02:01:12,000
people in Chicago. It was a lot of African Americans who voted with their feet for this guy named Kennedy.

1631
02:01:12,000 --> 02:01:17,000
Because they didn't know Kennedy from anybody else. A lot of them didn't like him because he was Catholic.

1632
02:01:17,000 --> 02:01:29,000
But King had become by then a symbol of change in the African American community. And that's why they switched over to Kennedy.

1633
02:01:30,000 --> 02:01:38,000
The historians have tried to minimize the arrest of King by giving it, most of the world just used earlier,

1634
02:01:38,000 --> 02:01:44,000
them in with faint praise. But the reality of it is that, but for that arrest, Nixon would have been president.

1635
02:01:44,000 --> 02:01:49,000
And all of the stuff could have been different. You know, had Nixon become president, okay?

1636
02:01:49,000 --> 02:02:04,000
I don't know. I wasn't that involved in that part of it. All I was trying to do was to put the issue of civil rights.

1637
02:02:04,000 --> 02:02:25,000
On the front pages of the People's Agenda for this country. And I figured that the person that could do it was King.

1638
02:02:25,000 --> 02:02:32,000
And I also felt that the students in Atlanta were organized until we could make it happen.

1639
02:02:32,000 --> 02:02:44,000
And of course, that is what happened. Interesting enough, though, I've learned as I've done more research lately.

1640
02:02:44,000 --> 02:02:56,000
Richard Nixon did prepare a statement to get involved with the situations and try to neutralize what Kennedy might have done.

1641
02:02:56,000 --> 02:03:09,000
Because he was going to call Alberta Williams King and he prepared a statement and gave it to E. Frederic Morrow, the black assistant to the president, during that time, to present Howard.

1642
02:03:09,000 --> 02:03:19,000
He said, let the old man read this statement because this is what I'm going to say. And when I was now a guy at the statement, he said no.

1643
02:03:19,000 --> 02:03:34,000
And so Nixon did do it because he didn't want to buck the boss. That was a fatal mistake on his part. Because what would have happened if Nixon and Kennedy both had spoken out against the injustice that was being perpetrated on King?

1644
02:03:34,000 --> 02:03:41,000
It might have neutralized the election and Nixon would probably have won.

1645
02:03:41,000 --> 02:03:48,000
I lost it.

1646
02:03:48,000 --> 02:03:51,000
How well organized it was?

1647
02:03:51,000 --> 02:04:08,000
Oh, yeah. Well, I think there were two things that were involved here. One is that I went to the middle chair and learned a lot about how to organize.

1648
02:04:08,000 --> 02:04:17,000
Plus, I grew up with people who were in the civil rights movement. They were down at the YMCA at the time and I listened as a boy.

1649
02:04:17,000 --> 02:04:32,000
Sucking all this stuff up. Plus, there was a guy who returned here and we called him El Comin Dante. He was a retired master's sergeant, I guess he was.

1650
02:04:32,000 --> 02:04:42,000
And he came by and asked me if he could work with us. And I told him, yes, he said, I'll work full time. No pay. I think it was a tie-dread.

1651
02:04:42,000 --> 02:04:58,000
And so Comin Dante came in and got with me and he was able to pull together a lot of blood. He put some meat on the bones that I had come up with.

1652
02:04:58,000 --> 02:05:09,000
He was not the one who put the ingredients together. He was the one who put the plan together. Like the end, you mentioned the two-way radio.

1653
02:05:09,000 --> 02:05:20,000
Let me tell you how that came about. Walkie Talkies. Every time we were done, the merchants had a survival strategy.

1654
02:05:20,000 --> 02:05:30,000
They assumed that if we came in and we probably came in by bus or we came in by car, once you close the lunch counter, we would go on about our business.

1655
02:05:30,000 --> 02:05:36,000
And so that was that tactic. When the students show up, don't arrest them, just close.

1656
02:05:36,000 --> 02:05:47,000
So our response to that was, it was a chess game. So our response was to get us some walkie talkies, two-way radios.

1657
02:05:47,000 --> 02:06:02,000
And we have teams of people who were downtown with radios in their car. At our communications headquarters on chessness street, we had, like a central, our lives, place that was where we could talk to all of them.

1658
02:06:02,000 --> 02:06:12,000
And so we had spotters. So let's assume for instance, Richard's department still closed the lunch counter, the the Magnolia Room.

1659
02:06:12,000 --> 02:06:19,000
So our people were going and leaving because they weren't going to arrest them. They knew they wanted to be arrested, so they weren't going to do that.

1660
02:06:19,000 --> 02:06:30,000
So when we leave, they'd open right back up, but what they didn't know was that we left centuries around and the walkie talkies.

1661
02:06:30,000 --> 02:06:41,000
And so what they would do is that they would call and say they just reopened again and send us was there. And we sent people right back in. They never figured out what we were doing.

1662
02:06:41,000 --> 02:06:59,000
And so we really harassed them so finally they just closed them all. But a guy named Ronald Yancey, Ronald Yancey and another guy who died on the Pueblo in Black and Stromes County, they developed that communication system for us.

1663
02:06:59,000 --> 02:07:07,000
And they actually ran it from over there. Ronald Yancey, he was by the way the first black person to finish Georgia Tech.

1664
02:07:07,000 --> 02:07:12,000
He lives up in Columbia, Maryland now. He's retired.

1665
02:07:12,000 --> 02:07:27,000
Many instances telling you, and I saw a little news that the clip about it, that absolute one year's of reunification has to be at the decision of handing down that the land of things have been so reunified.

1666
02:07:28,000 --> 02:07:46,000
Well, here let me go into that. On about the 4th of December 1960, the court ruled in Boynton v. Virginia that you shouldn't have discrimination in the interstate commerce on these buses and trains.

1667
02:07:46,000 --> 02:07:58,000
So we had a committee meeting in the next day or two and we were discussing that issue. And so we decided that we would go and test Boynton v. Virginia.

1668
02:07:58,000 --> 02:08:11,000
We sent a team to Chattanooga, Columbia, South Carolina, Jacksonville, Florida, Birmingham, Alabama.

1669
02:08:12,000 --> 02:08:20,000
Yeah. Marion and her sister, I think, went to Birmingham, I believe.

1670
02:08:20,000 --> 02:08:24,000
And got arrested, I think when he got back to Atlanta. Yeah.

1671
02:08:24,000 --> 02:08:36,000
Mr. Maurice Pennington, the same artist, and his nephew and Mays Dillard went to Chattanooga and got arrested.

1672
02:08:37,000 --> 02:08:52,000
Norma June Wilson, and I've forgotten who went with her now, went to Jacksonville and they got arrested, now they're making Charles A. Black and Otis Moss Jr, who you might talk to later on.

1673
02:08:52,000 --> 02:09:01,000
They went to South Carolina. They were histled up in Athens, but they were not arrested.

1674
02:09:02,000 --> 02:09:11,000
The idea was to test this decision. Claude Sitton, you remember him?

1675
02:09:11,000 --> 02:09:20,000
Claude Sitton wrote in the New York Times a few days later about the city.

1676
02:09:20,000 --> 02:09:27,000
I know it was written, I don't have it, I can probably get it though, okay?

1677
02:09:28,000 --> 02:09:35,000
But he did write it. And James Farmer called me and asked me, he told me more about it.

1678
02:09:35,000 --> 02:09:45,000
And I told him, he said, well, you know, I tried this earlier. He said several years ago, I didn't even get too far with him.

1679
02:09:45,000 --> 02:09:53,000
We did it kind of up on the other side of the nation, the nation of Dixon and Lyon. He said, I think maybe we want to do it.

1680
02:09:53,000 --> 02:09:58,000
I said, okay, I said, well, when you're going to do it, he said, I'm going to do it in the spring.

1681
02:09:58,000 --> 02:10:05,000
So he said, remember you're going to come through Atlanta. I said, when you get to Atlanta and get your call,

1682
02:10:05,000 --> 02:10:16,000
and I'll come and talk to you on. And sure enough, when you got here, we went over to Clark College where they were standing, we did talk to him.

1683
02:10:16,000 --> 02:10:21,000
I was looked at the NAACP files recently in that the Library of Congress.

1684
02:10:21,000 --> 02:10:34,000
And there's a letter in there for Marvin Rich, remember him? Marvin Rich to Roy Wilkins, detailing how they were planning the Freedom Rides in the spring.

1685
02:10:34,000 --> 02:10:40,000
That letter was in February of 1961.

1686
02:10:41,000 --> 02:10:47,000
The answer question, yes, we had the first one. It was the first one, I guess it was in modern times.

1687
02:10:47,000 --> 02:10:55,000
James Farmer had done it earlier back in the 40s. That's right.

1688
02:10:55,000 --> 02:11:02,000
But I think it was outside the South, though. Right.

1689
02:11:02,000 --> 02:11:07,000
But we have pictures of all of that.

1690
02:11:07,000 --> 02:11:16,000
We have pictures that will be a part of the exhibit. Pictures of Norma June, Wilson, and Marion, and Norma June, Marion.

1691
02:11:16,000 --> 02:11:22,000
And I believe we may have him appinant in two. And I think they have a receipt.

1692
02:11:22,000 --> 02:11:26,000
All that's going to be there.

1693
02:11:26,000 --> 02:11:33,000
Yeah, yeah, it's going to be there. But these are the things that have not been brought out, but we're going to have more with that though.

1694
02:11:33,000 --> 02:11:42,000
I mean, I know one of the things that has been written about a lot,

1695
02:11:42,000 --> 02:11:49,000
that's the relationship between the students and the adults.

1696
02:11:49,000 --> 02:11:54,000
I called my 19-year-old grandson who came in.

1697
02:11:54,000 --> 02:11:57,000
Okay, we're back.

1698
02:11:57,000 --> 02:12:03,000
You know, what happened in the spring of 1961, and I don't know,

1699
02:12:03,000 --> 02:12:08,000
but it compromised. I don't know if that's something you want to talk about.

1700
02:12:08,000 --> 02:12:14,000
I'll be happy to talk to you about it. On the 1st of February, 1960,

1701
02:12:14,000 --> 02:12:20,000
well, no. Back during the fall campaign, the Chamber of Commerce types,

1702
02:12:20,000 --> 02:12:27,000
in the mayor, all of them got all involved in China's settlers, but the white merchants were not agreed.

1703
02:12:27,000 --> 02:12:41,000
The powers that be in the white community wanted to try to see if they could find a way to settle the situation on their terms,

1704
02:12:41,000 --> 02:12:44,000
on terms both labeled with them.

1705
02:12:44,000 --> 02:12:49,000
And so there are a series of meetings out in the black community,

1706
02:12:49,000 --> 02:12:55,000
on with these Negro leaders, who were not in charge of the movement that were going to be negotiating for us.

1707
02:12:55,000 --> 02:12:59,000
Well, once they put all these plans together,

1708
02:12:59,000 --> 02:13:07,000
as well as they were going to integrate everything, after the schools deserigated in the fall.

1709
02:13:07,000 --> 02:13:14,000
No, after the schools deserigated, not in the fall, but whenever they did it.

1710
02:13:14,000 --> 02:13:20,000
The someone said in that meeting, I wasn't there, but I was told by State Sen. Leroy Johnson.

1711
02:13:20,000 --> 02:13:26,000
Someone said, well, who's going to say, we don't control the students.

1712
02:13:26,000 --> 02:13:29,000
They won't even meet with us when they're going to do strategy.

1713
02:13:29,000 --> 02:13:34,000
So, how are they going to tell a line of king? We can't do it unless we get him involved.

1714
02:13:34,000 --> 02:13:40,000
Did you know they were having meetings? No, no, no, they were doing it behind my back.

1715
02:13:40,000 --> 02:13:47,000
So, Jesse Hill Jr said, well, I can get him to come to a meeting.

1716
02:13:47,000 --> 02:13:52,000
And they said, can you get him to a meeting? He said, well, he trusts me.

1717
02:13:52,000 --> 02:13:57,000
I can get him to come. And sure enough, Jesse Hill Jr called me to ask me to come to this meeting,

1718
02:13:57,000 --> 02:14:00,000
the chain of commerce.

1719
02:14:00,000 --> 02:14:05,000
Most important meeting of your life. I said, what is it about, Jesse?

1720
02:14:05,000 --> 02:14:11,000
Trust me, trust me. And so, I said, okay.

1721
02:14:11,000 --> 02:14:17,000
So, when I got to the meeting, here were all these powers that I've been battling,

1722
02:14:17,000 --> 02:14:22,000
along with the black leaders that were pushed to the side because they didn't have the troops.

1723
02:14:22,000 --> 02:14:25,000
I had the troops, you follow me?

1724
02:14:25,000 --> 02:14:33,000
And so, they presented to me the proposition.

1725
02:14:33,000 --> 02:14:39,000
They were going to integrate by this time, now, that's a court decision that the schools have to integrate by fall.

1726
02:14:39,000 --> 02:14:46,000
See, they first had those meetings in the late December, January, but then the court ruled.

1727
02:14:46,000 --> 02:14:53,000
And so, they were going to do it now after the schools opened, deserigated.

1728
02:14:53,000 --> 02:14:58,000
And so, they wanted a verbal agreement with me to do that.

1729
02:14:58,000 --> 02:15:02,000
So, nothing I can do that.

1730
02:15:02,000 --> 02:15:09,000
So, Martin Luther King Sr jumped up and he said, I'm tired of you, boy.

1731
02:15:09,000 --> 02:15:16,000
You're going to wreck this time. I baptized you.

1732
02:15:16,000 --> 02:15:23,000
And so, I just ignored it. And the iron never old, Dr. Emilye Crosby,

1733
02:15:23,000 --> 02:15:32,000
is that the man who came to my defense in that meeting was a man named Frank H. Neely,

1734
02:15:32,000 --> 02:15:36,000
who was the chairman of the board of Richard's department store,

1735
02:15:36,000 --> 02:15:41,000
who was sitting directly across from me and had been hitting me on my leg with his cane.

1736
02:15:41,000 --> 02:15:46,000
He said that, he said, Rubbin King, he's the only one who has a constituents.

1737
02:15:46,000 --> 02:15:50,000
He was elected. We all appointed ourselves.

1738
02:15:50,000 --> 02:15:56,000
Because, I said, let me take this proposition back to the group that I'm representing.

1739
02:15:56,000 --> 02:16:01,000
And that's what upset King, okay?

1740
02:16:01,000 --> 02:16:06,000
I was snookered into a chamber of commerce meeting.

1741
02:16:06,000 --> 02:16:11,000
For some reason, I was thinking that it was a meeting that was with the Black leaders.

1742
02:16:11,000 --> 02:16:16,000
No, no, the Black leaders were meeting with representatives separately.

1743
02:16:16,000 --> 02:16:19,000
But then they pulled us meeting together because they had to get King,

1744
02:16:19,000 --> 02:16:23,000
and you had to get me into it.

1745
02:16:23,000 --> 02:16:27,000
Herschelle Sullivan joined me. I asked her to come with me, right?

1746
02:16:27,000 --> 02:16:32,000
She didn't even say, but she was there. I wanted witness.

1747
02:16:32,000 --> 02:16:41,000
Well, when Neely made that comment that I was not wrong,

1748
02:16:41,000 --> 02:16:49,000
Ivan Allen Jr Jr and A.T. Walden call for recess.

1749
02:16:49,000 --> 02:16:55,000
And this time, Rufus E. Clement came over to me,

1750
02:16:55,000 --> 02:16:58,000
and he's the president of the AU. He came over and said,

1751
02:16:58,000 --> 02:17:01,000
you were trying to rock in a hard place. I said, yeah.

1752
02:17:01,000 --> 02:17:05,000
He said, you damned if you do, you damned if you don't.

1753
02:17:05,000 --> 02:17:08,000
And that's all he said.

1754
02:17:08,000 --> 02:17:13,000
KB Williamson said, I don't know what to tell you. That was a real statement.

1755
02:17:13,000 --> 02:17:18,000
And then it overcomes one of my great, and I was a great admirer of mine,

1756
02:17:18,000 --> 02:17:20,000
and I was a great admirer of him.

1757
02:17:20,000 --> 02:17:24,000
Mr. John C. Calhoun, who had been the head of the NAACP,

1758
02:17:24,000 --> 02:17:27,000
with gone to jail rather than give up the NAACP list of the governor,

1759
02:17:27,000 --> 02:17:34,000
who's one of the father's teachers. He says, learning,

1760
02:17:34,000 --> 02:17:39,000
I think you ought to go along with this. I said, why?

1761
02:17:39,000 --> 02:17:42,000
You saw you were aware of that. This is the first time

1762
02:17:42,000 --> 02:17:45,000
that we've ever been able to get white folks in the South to agree

1763
02:17:45,000 --> 02:17:49,000
to voluntary do a whole set of disarrigation without it being mandated

1764
02:17:49,000 --> 02:17:53,000
by the federal courts. I said, yeah, I'm aware of that.

1765
02:17:54,000 --> 02:18:01,000
He said, I'm 60 years old, and I have been

1766
02:18:01,000 --> 02:18:04,000
still getting every day of my life.

1767
02:18:04,000 --> 02:18:08,000
And if I have to wait for March to September,

1768
02:18:08,000 --> 02:18:12,000
when I can go downtown and do, anywhere I want to eat,

1769
02:18:12,000 --> 02:18:17,000
spend my money without being put into the back or put into color section,

1770
02:18:17,000 --> 02:18:22,000
he said, that's a short time. He said, I know you don't like it.

1771
02:18:22,000 --> 02:18:27,000
But I recommend that's one of your advice that you go along with it.

1772
02:18:27,000 --> 02:18:34,000
I thought about it, and I said, when we reconvene, I said,

1773
02:18:34,000 --> 02:18:39,000
I will go along with this on two conditions, one that is in writing,

1774
02:18:39,000 --> 02:18:45,000
and two that I also be able to go and present it to my students.

1775
02:18:45,000 --> 02:18:49,000
And that was kind of the way the thing ended.

1776
02:18:49,000 --> 02:18:55,000
When we left the meeting, and before I could get back to the school,

1777
02:18:55,000 --> 02:18:58,000
Ivan Allen Jr Jr had held a press conference.

1778
02:18:58,000 --> 02:19:02,000
I guess he had to press out there in the anti-group somewhere.

1779
02:19:02,000 --> 02:19:14,000
He announced that the NIGRA student leaders have agreed to end the boycott,

1780
02:19:15,000 --> 02:19:21,000
and that the lunch count was open to be open tomorrow segregated.

1781
02:19:21,000 --> 02:19:23,000
And that was all he had to say.

1782
02:19:23,000 --> 02:19:27,000
Man, that was a firestorm in this town.

1783
02:19:27,000 --> 02:19:31,000
I mean, a literal firestorm.

1784
02:19:31,000 --> 02:19:38,000
That was when I think the whole town realized that the community had backed us,

1785
02:19:38,000 --> 02:19:43,000
and they were upset because they knew that we were probably close to victory.

1786
02:19:44,000 --> 02:19:50,000
So I went back and presented it to the students, and her shell and I resigned,

1787
02:19:50,000 --> 02:19:54,000
because we've been really just pressured into this mess.

1788
02:19:54,000 --> 02:19:56,000
Did you, when you followed the deadline,

1789
02:19:56,000 --> 02:20:02,000
you coming back to the team, and you were going to get the news going?

1790
02:20:02,000 --> 02:20:04,000
No, I did not.

1791
02:20:04,000 --> 02:20:09,000
I just went back, and I resigned, her shell resigned.

1792
02:20:09,000 --> 02:20:14,000
And the students unanimously refused to accept our resignation.

1793
02:20:14,000 --> 02:20:16,000
So you've taken us this far?

1794
02:20:16,000 --> 02:20:19,000
Let's call a mass meeting and see what the public thinks.

1795
02:20:19,000 --> 02:20:26,000
So we call a mass meeting for the 10th of March at Warren Memorial Methodist Church,

1796
02:20:26,000 --> 02:20:29,000
not at rest at all.

